[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hello! I'm Grandmaster Mircea Parligras, the Romanian 2022 Champion!  I'll be your guide to uncovering the wonderful world of the Ragozin, with all its resources, plans, and ideas! I'm a long-time Ragozin player with both colors. In this course, I will show you some of the lines I played in practice, with lots of improvements, of course!  The Ragozin can be reached via different move orders-   1.c4  e6  2.Nc3  d5  3.d4  Bb4  4.Nf3  Nf6  ,   1.c4  Nf6  2.Nf3  e6  3.Nc3  d5  4.d4  Bb4  ,   1.Nf3  Nf6  2.d4  d5  3.c4  e6  4.Nc3  Bb4  and many others.  The Ragozin Defense is named after the Soviet Grandmaster Viacheslav Ragozin 1908-1962 who made big contributions to this opening. It offers Black active play from the start and it fits well with the repertoire of the Nimzo players. }
1. d4
{ The second most played move after  1.e4  . White is fighting for the center. }
1... Nf6
{ A logical developing move controlling the center and stopping e4.  This is what I usually play in practice because I don't mind playing the Nimzo.  1...d5  is another way, and after  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Bb4  4.Nf3  Nf6  it leads to the Ragozin, but White has other options on move 4 like   4.a3  or  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bf4  .  Another way to reach the Ragozin is after   3...Nf6  4.Nf3  Bb4  , but again White can play   4.cxd5  which leads to something else. }
2. c4 { The most principled move, preventing ...d5 and preparing Nc3. } 2... e6
{ The fight for the center continues - we're ready to play ...d5 or ...Bb4. }
3. Nf3
{ This is a useful developing move, after  3...Bb4+  White can go  4.Bd2  or  4.Nbd2  ,  4.Nc3  d5  would be another move order to reach the Ragozin.  The immediate   3.Nc3  would lead into the Nimzo after  3...Bb4  , but  4.Nf3  d5  gets us into the Ragozin again, although Black has other options as well like  4...b6  ,  4...c5  , or  4...O-O  . }
3... d5 { We get a foothold in the center. } 4. Nc3
{ A very principled move, fighting for the center. White aims to play Bg5 and e3. }
4... Bb4
{ And we get into the Ragozin! We're pinning the white knight in order to actively fight for the center.  In this course I covered all of White's possibilities from here - the main line is  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Bg5  , where I offer 2 good possibilities.  Against the fashionable   5.cxd5  exd5  6.Bf4  I give 2 less known but good options, again.  We also examine the most often seen move   5.Bg5  , the interesting  5.Qa4+  , the Nimzo after  5.e3  , the Nimzo after  5.g3  , and the solid  5.Qb3  .  I will give many examples from my own games and share my experiences with the Ragozin. It's a solid and active opening, and I like it because Black has good control over the center. It's also more lively than the Queen's Gambit Accepted, which I also tried.  My view for this course is to give some fresh and sometimes less explored ideas so that your opponents start thinking early on. Also, I tried to avoid long forced lines, where if you don't remember a move it's over. Instead, I found a balance between sharp lines and strategic play, giving White plenty of chances to go wrong.  I wrote this course for a wide range of players, from beginners to GMs. There are plenty of explanations after each move - I strive to show and explain clearly the ideas in each position. I also showed the plans with visuals to help you remember the lines easier.  Don't worry if you don't remember the moves or some lines - the positions are sound and general ideas will get you going in the game.  Thank you for studying this course! I hope you will enjoy it and that the Ragozin will become a long-term weapon in your repertoire. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "1) 6.Bg5 with 7.Bh4 Nbd7 8.Qc2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5
{ A principled move, and one of the main lines. White aims for a harmonious development by either Bg5 or Bf4 followed by e3, Bd3. On the other hand, our light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
5... exd5 6. Bg5
{ The most principled move, pinning our knight.   6.Qc2  transposes to 5. Qc2. }
6... h6
{ A useful move. If the bishop retreats to h4 we'll have the option to push g5. }
7. Bh4 { White keeps the bishop and the pressure. } 7... Nbd7
{ This is my main recommendation. The idea is to play ...g5 next and then ...Ne4. If White forces us to take on g3, the d7-knight will be useful because it can go to either f6 or b6, and we won't be lagging much in development. }
8. Qc2
{ A flexible move. White is defending the knight in advance and only then is going to develop with e3 and Bd3. }
8... g5
{ We continue our plan of grabbing the dark-squared bishop. The other main move is ...c5, but that's a different setup than the one I'm recommending. }
9. Bg3 Ne4
{ That was the point. If White doesn't challenge our central knight quickly, we're going to push ...h5-h4 to harass the g3-bishop. }
10. Nd2 { A typical reply - White gets rid of our central knight. } 10... Nxg3
{ We need to exchange the dark-squared bishop. } 11. hxg3 Nb6
{ Thus Black is better prepared against e4.  11...c6  transposes to the line with 7... g5. }
12. a3 { This makes sense. Depending on our reply White can continue with e4. }
12... Bf8 { The best place for the bishop in case White goes for e4. } 13. e3
c6 { This is useful. } 14. Nb3 { To keep ideas of Nc5. } 14... Qf6
{ One of the many possible options.  14...Bg7  was also interesting. } 15. Bd3
Be6
{ With a typical position for this line. If we castle long, it's good to have the bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal, to keep c5 under control. }
