[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4) 5.cxd5 with 6.Bf4 Ne4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5
{ A principled move, and one of the main lines. White aims for a harmonious development by either Bg5 or Bf4 followed by e3, Bd3. On the other hand, our light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
5... exd5 6. Bf4
{ This line is quite fashionable, and I also used it successfully a few times. White wants to develop the pieces with e3, Bd3 and O-O without having to deal with ...h6 and ...g5 like in the Bg5 lines.I decided to give 2 alternatives for Black here because Bf4 is quite fashionable nowadays. Both lines are sound and may have a surprise effect on your opponent! }
6... Ne4 7. Rc1 { Defends the knight. } 7... Nd7
{ An interesting idea. The knight is more flexible here than on c6 and can go to b6.  7...Nc6  is the most played move, but let's surprise our opponent! }
8. e3 { A natural developing move that doesn't take into account our ideas. }
8... g5 { Whenever possible we go chasing this bishop. } 9. Be5
{ It's not easy to understand why this is better than Bg3. The point is that after  9...f6  10.Bg3  h5  11.h4  White is better due to the misplaced pawn on f6. }
9... O-O
{ Now the white bishop has no scope and we can take it at the right moment. }
10. Bd3 Bxc3+ { It's useful to include this first. } 11. bxc3 g4
{ The idea is to dislodge the white knight and then take on e5. } 12. Nd2 Nxe5
{ According to the plan. } 13. dxe5 Qe7 14. O-O
{ White is trying to complicate matters. After  14.Nxe4  dxe4  15.Bxe4  Qxe5  Black has no problems. }
14... Nxd2
{ One of the good options in the position. It was also possible to take the pawn directly  14...Qxe5  . }
15. Qxd2 Qxe5
{ White has compensation for the pawn but nothing more. Although our king is a bit exposed, I don't see how White can take advantage of it. A sample line goes  16.f4  gxf3  17.Rxf3  Bg4  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4) 5.cxd5 with 6.Bf4 O-O (Alternative)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5
{ A principled move, and one of the main lines. White aims for a harmonious development by either Bg5 or Bf4 followed by e3, Bd3. On the other hand, our light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
5... exd5 6. Bf4
{ This line is quite fashionable, and I also used it successfully a few times. White wants to develop the pieces with e3, Bd3 and O-O without having to deal with ...h6 and ...g5 like in the Bg5 lines.I decided to give 2 alternatives for Black here because Bf4 is quite fashionable nowadays. Both lines are sound and may have a surprise effect on your opponent! }
6... O-O
{ I give this as an alternative to ...Ne4 followed by ...Nd7. Our idea is to break the center with ...c5. }
7. e3 c5 { A principled break in the center. } 8. dxc5 Qa5
{ Here we need to show some accuracy. This is good because we can meet  9.Rc1  with  9...Qxa2  . }
9. Nd2 { Covers the pin and intends either Rc1 or Nb3. } 9... Nc6
{ This is interesting because we have the strong threat of ...d4.  9...Bxc3  10.bxc3  Qxc5  is a sound alternative. }
10. Nb3
{ The logical follow-up.  10.Bd6?  would be a mistake in view of  10...d4!  with a winning position. }
10... Bxc3+ { Forced. } 11. bxc3 Qxc3+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2
{ So far we followed an online game between Carlsen and Aronian. } 13... d4
{ Aronian continued with ...Ne4+ followed by ...g5 which was good enough. However, this is a more direct way to play the position. }
14. Nxd4 Rd8
{ We're going to take back the pawn. The position is about equal. White has the bishop pair, but his king is exposed and the c5-pawn can sometimes become a target. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "5) 5.Qa4+ with 6.e3 & 7.Qc2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+
{ This check is one of the main lines in the Ragozin. White forces us to play ...Nc6 and claims the knight is slightly misplaced there - it's not so easy to push ...c5, but ...dxc4 and ...e5 becomes a viable idea. The white queen usually goes back later on. }
5... Nc6 6. e3 O-O 7. Qc2
{ The queen did its job to lure the knight to c6 and now returns to a better square. }
7... dxc4
{ This is my main suggestion, a move I already played several times. The point is to clear out the center by playing ...Bd6 and ...e5 we cannot play ...Bd6 immediately because White goes c5.   7...Re8  is played often here I even tried it once. However, I think Black needs to be precise there. The move I recommend is more clear cut. }
8. Bxc4 Bd6 { A necessary regrouping in order to prepare ...e5. } 9. O-O e5 10.
d5 { Not the best moment for this. } 10... Nb4
{ Here there is this extra option. Of course, there is nothing wrong with  10...Ne7  , but we can also fight for an advantage. }
11. Qb1
{ Only here.  11.Qd2  is just bad in view of  11...e4  12.Nd4  Bxh2+!  13.Kxh2  Ng4+  winning. }
11... e4 { The move we're counting on. } 12. Nxe4 { Forced. } 12... Nxe4 13.
Qxe4 Re8
{ It turns out the white queen doesn't have good squares -  14.Qh4?  fails to  14...Qxh4  15.Nxh4  Re4  and White loses a piece. }
14. Qb1 { Only here. } 14... Bg4 { With an initiative for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "5) 5.Qa4+ with 6.e3 & 7.Bd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+
{ This check is one of the main lines in the Ragozin. White forces us to play ...Nc6 and claims the knight is slightly misplaced there - it's not so easy to push ...c5, but ...dxc4 and ...e5 becomes a viable idea. The white queen usually goes back later on. }
5... Nc6 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd2 { A principled developing move, addressing the pin. }
7... dxc4
{ We want to retreat the bishop to d6 and play ...a6. Afterwards we go for ...e5. }
8. Bxc4 a6
{ I like to include this move in order to keep the option to push ...b5 at any time. A fine point of it is that it prevents Nb5. Afterwards, we will proceed with ...Bd6 and then either ...e5 or ...b5.   8...Bd6  is played most often here, and it can transpose to our lines if we go afterwards ...a6. }
9. Qc2
{ The most often played move. The queen did its job to lure our knight to c6 and now returns to a better spot. }
9... Bd6
{ We regrouped our bishop. Now besides the typical idea ...e5, there is also the more ambitious ...b5. }
10. O-O b5 { It makes sense to start our play on the queenside. } 11. Be2
{ The best available square for the bishop.   11.Bd3  is answered by  11...Nb4  12.Qb1  Nxd3  . }
11... Bb7 12. e4 { This push rather plays into our hands. } 12... e5
{ I already prefer Black here. } *

