[Black "7) 5.Bg5 with 7.Qb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5
{ One of the main moves to fight against the Ragozin. The pin is principled, and by not taking on d5 Black's c8-bishop remains shut off. The downside is that the c4-pawn is hanging. }
5... h6
{ By far the most played move. If the bishop retreats to h4 then it's good to take on c4. In over the board games, I also tried  5...dxc4  , transposing to a Vienna. However, I decided against recommending that because some lines are too forced, and if you forget some detail it can be decisive. }
6. Bxf6
{ White gives up the bishop and goes for a strategic approach. He has good control in the center, while we still have to find a way to develop the light-squared bishop. }
6... Qxf6 7. Qb3
{ A solid system, where White tries to play for a slight advantage. } 7... c5
{ We need to fight for the center. We may have to sacrifice a pawn to complete development, but Black is doing fine. }
8. cxd5
{ It makes sense to trade the pawns. Maybe White can delay this a bit with  8.e3  O-O  but then after  9.cxd5  exd5  it will transpose.   8.dxc5  is not so good because of  8...Bxc3+  . }
8... exd5 9. a3 { This line is not fashionable anymore. } 9... Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3
c4
{ The most accurate, also played by Magnus Carlsen. We're gaining space on the queenside. However, in case you don't remember the details during a game, there is nothing wrong with  10...Nd7  11.e3  O-O  12.Be2   12.Bb5  is well met by  12...c4!  12...Rb8!?  preparing ...b5  13.a4  a6  14.O-O  c4  followed by ...b5. }
11. b3 { White has to fight against the pawn chain as soon as possible. } 11...
Be6 { We defend the pawn. } 12. bxc4
{ White continues his idea of undermining Black's pawn chain. } 12... dxc4 13.
e4
{ White got a nice center, but we have enough resources to fight against it. }
13... O-O
{ It turns out the c4-pawn cannot be captured, and White's central pawns cannot advance yet. }
14. Be2 Re8
{ It's important to remember this precise move. The rook is very useful here, and now we're ready for ...Nc6. Note that the immediate  14...Nc6?  would be wrong due to  15.Rc1! }
15. O-O
{ White will soon be ready to attack the c4-pawn and will also try to roll up the central pawns. }
15... Nc6
{ We have finished development just in time. Now we have different ideas like ...b5 to defend c4, ...Rad8 to attack d4, or ...Qf4. }
16. Rac1
{ Threatens d5.  16.Rab1  can be met with  ...Rad8  , or   16.Rfe1  with  ...b5  . }
16... Qf4
{ Black is fine. We're going to get the e4-pawn, thus destroying White's center. Play may continue  17.d5  Qxe4  18.dxe6  Qxe2  19.exf7+  Kxf7  20.Qxc4+  Qxc4  21.Rxc4  Rac8  with equality. }
