[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. e3
{ A classical approach, White reverts to the Nimzowitsch with e3.   It's a solid setup, but it will take some time to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
5... O-O
{ A flexible move. We'll decide on the next steps depending on what White does. }
6. Bd2 { An old plan that gained a lot of popularity recently. } 6... b6
{ By far the main move here, we're going to fianchetto the bishop.  Another interesting idea is  6...Nbd7!?  , in order to make it less attractive for White to take on d5. }
7. cxd5
{ Once we played ...b6, White goes for this.   The point is quite simple- we won't develop the bishop on the c8-h3 diagonal because of the weak white squares on the queenside. }
7... exd5 8. Bd3 { White wants to develop as quickly as possible. } 8... Bb7
{ Once we have played ...b6 the bishop belongs here. } 9. O-O
{ 9.Ne5  is a bit early and after  9...Bd6  we're going to follow up with ...c5 and ...Nc6. }
9... Bd6
{ The bishop is more active here than on e7. Without the rook on c1 White doesn't have Nb5, attacking both the bishop and c7-pawn - we simply retreat the bishop to e7. }
10. Ne5
{ The principled move. White is going to support this knight in the center with f4. }
10... c5
{ We have to act quickly. We're going to develop the knight to c6 and attack the d4-pawn. }
11. f4 { White supports the knight and prepares the typical maneuver Be1-h4. }
11... Nc6 { The threat to take on d4 is real. } 12. Ng4
{ A typical maneuver which turns out to be an instructive mistake here. } 12...
Be7
{ Very strong. It completely stops White's threat,   12...--  13.Nxf6  Qxf6  14.Nxd5  ,  while d4 is still hanging. }
13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 { The bishop is ideally placed here. } 14. dxc5
{ The only way to save the pawn. } 14... bxc5 15. Rc1 Re8
{ Black got an excellent position and went on to win in Ciolacu, A 2199 - Jianu, V 2527 Targu Mures 2022. }
