[Black "11) 5.g3 with 8.Qa4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. g3
{ The fianchetto is always an option. White aims for a long time pressure in Catalan style. However, here ...Bb4 and Nc3 favour us. We're going to grab the c4-pawn and then hang onto it. }
5... O-O
{ A natural reply - the c4-move is not going anywhere. It's not favourable for White to trade the pawns on d5 as it opens up our light-squared bishop. However,  5...dxc4  is the same. }
6. Bg2 dxc4
{ We take the pawn. It's not easy for White to take back the pawn because of the c3-knight. }
7. O-O
{ The most natural move. In the Catalan, White usually develops the kingside and then tries his best to get the pawn back. }
7... Nc6
{ A useful move - it puts some pressure on the white center, and prevents Ne5. }
8. Qa4
{ A multi-purpose move. It prepares Bg5 and Rd1, but there is also the direct threat of Ne5. }
8... Nd5
{ This is intended to take advantage of the queen's exposed position. } 9. Qc2
{ Threatens e4 with tempo. } 9... Be7
{ This looks like a dance of the pieces back and forth. We want to meet e4 with ...Ndb4. }
10. Rd1 { Prepares e4 anyway, but the d4-pawn had to be defended first. } 10...
Rb8 { We're going to support the c4-pawn! } 11. e4 Ndb4
{ This looks natural.  11...Ncb4  12.Qb1  Nxc3  13.bxc3  Nd3  is possible as well. We'd lose the c4-pawn after  14.Qb5  , but trade some pieces on the way. }
12. Qb1 { The queen is too hidden here. } 12... Nd3 { We continue our idea. }
13. Be3 b5 14. d5
{ White has to do something, otherwise, he's just a pawn down. } 14... exd5 15.
exd5
{ This was played in Stankovic, M 2468 - Parligras, M 2607 Hungary 2019. }
15... Na5
{ It was essential to put the knight here in order to get an advantage. The game continued with the tempting  15...Ncb4  , but after  16.a3  Nxd5  17.Nxd5  Qxd5  18.Ne1  the position was equal. }
16. Bxa7 { What else? } 16... Ra8 17. Be3 Bf5
{ With a nice position for Black due to the great knight on d3. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "11) 5.g3 with 8.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. g3
{ The fianchetto is always an option. White aims for a long time pressure in Catalan style. However, here ...Bb4 and Nc3 favour us. We're going to grab the c4-pawn and then hang onto it. }
5... O-O
{ A natural reply - the c4-move is not going anywhere. It's not favourable for White to trade the pawns on d5 as it opens up our light-squared bishop. However,  5...dxc4  is the same. }
6. Bg2 dxc4
{ We take the pawn. It's not easy for White to take back the pawn because of the c3-knight. }
7. O-O
{ The most natural move. In the Catalan, White usually develops the kingside and then tries his best to get the pawn back. }
7... Nc6
{ A useful move - it puts some pressure on the white center, and prevents Ne5. }
8. a3
{ The main move. Now in the case of the trade on c3, we don't have ...c5 anymore. }
8... Be7
{ It looks best to keep the bishop and also the c4-pawn!. }
9. e4 { White gets a nice center, but for now cannot get the pawn back. } 9...
a6
{ We want to reinforce the pawn chain with ...b5. I also looked at  9...Na5  , but I think the text is better. }
10. Be3
{ It's good to defend the d4-pawn in advance. The drawback is that Black can get ...Ng4 with tempo at some point. }
10... b5
{ We continue our idea. Now White has to decide how to fight for the initiative. }
11. Qc2
{ A good place for the queen. After e5 and Ng5 there is a mate threat on h7. White can also reinforce the center with Rad1 preparing the d5 push. }
11... Bb7 { We continue development. } 12. Rad1
{ It frees up the bishop and the knight from defending the d4-pawn, and it also prepares the advance d5. }
12... Na5 { This is aimed against d5. Given time the knight can go to b3. } 13.
d5 { The prepared break in the center. } 13... Qe8
{ We remove the queen from the dangerous file. We are a pawn up, but the position is complicated. Black is doing fine, but we still need to be more careful for the next moves. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "12) 5.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. a3
{ Basically White tries to bring the game into new territory. It's played more often in blitz and internet games. }
5... Bxc3+ { There is no reason to retreat the bishop. } 6. bxc3 c5
{ In these kinds of positions we want to break the center, so we're going to do it right away.  Of course, there is nothing wrong with  6...O-O  . }
7. cxd5 exd5 8. g3 { Aiming for an original setup. } 8... O-O 9. Bg2 Re8
{ Of course, other moves are possible as well, like  9...Nc6  or  9...Ne4  . }
10. O-O Ne4 { The knight has an excellent spot in the center. } 11. Qc2 cxd4
{ It seems good to trade the pawns before going ...Nc6, to prevent dxc5. } 12.
Nxd4 Nc6
{ Black's active pieces compensate for White's bishop-pair, besides White has no breaks.  After  13.Rd1  we will play  13...Na5  , stopping c4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "12) 5.Qb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qb3
{ This is one of the most solid replies for White in the Ragozin, and we will find out why soon. }
5... c5
{ The most common and logical move, we defend the bishop and fight for the center at the same time. }
6. dxc5 { The most often played move, the threat on the bishop is renewed. }
6... Nc6
{ One of two good moves in this position, the other being  6...Na6  , but I prefer  6...Nc6  because the knight has a more natural position here. }
7. Bg5 { White is counting on this pin. } 7... Qa5
{ An active move putting pressure on the a5-e1 diagonal.  Note that  7...dxc4  followed by ...Qa5 is the same thing. }
8. Bxf6 dxc4
{ It's important to remember this zwischenzug, otherwise White can take on d5 and spoil our pawn structure. }
9. Qxc4 gxf6 10. Rc1
{ Secures the c3-knight. Afterward White completes development and then will try to play against our doubled pawns. }
10... Qxc5 { Of course, we take back the pawn. } 11. Qf4
{ White keeps the queen closer to the center, defends the rook on c1, and sometimes keeps the threat of Qc7+ in reserve. }
11... Ke7
{ The king feels good here.  Note that  12.Qc7+  is not a threat at the moment, but we may have to watch out for it a bit later. }
12. g3
{ White continues development and wants to put pressure on the long diagonal. }
12... Bxc3+
{ It was also possible to play  12...e5  but it seems a bit more complicated, so I prefer to see how White reacts to this. }
13. bxc3
{ White spoils the pawn structure, but now it's not so easy for us to trade the queens. }
13... Bd7
{ The bishop is quite active here.   We cannot play ...b6 and ...Bb7 anymore because of Qc7+. But ...b6 with ...Ba6 is possible as well. }
14. Bg2 Rac8 { We want the rook on this half-open file. } 15. O-O
{ Just finishing development. } 15... b6
{ We're preparing ...Ne5 and for that, we need the b-pawn out of danger. } 16.
Rfd1 { Rxd7+ followed by Qxf6 is a threat. } 16... Ne5
{ Forcing a series of exchanges.  16...Rhd8  is a bit hurried because it leaves the h7-pawn undefended. }
17. Rd4
{ With the idea to double the rooks.   17.Nd4  can be met with  17...Rhd8  , when Black is doing fine because everything is defended. }
17... Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 Rhd8
{ We finally bring the last piece into play. Black's position is strategically sound, but there are still a few tactical details on the table.  A possible continuation is  19.Rcd1  e5  20.Rxd7+  Rxd7  21.Rxd7+  Kxd7  22.Qxf6  and now the precise move  22...Qc4  gives us good play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 5.cxd5 exd5 6.Bg5 h6 7.Bh4 − 7...Nbd7 Main Line"]
[Black "7.Bh4 Nbd7 8.Nd2 with 9.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5
{ A principled move, and one of the main lines. White aims for a harmonious development by either Bg5 or Bf4 followed by e3, Bd3. On the other hand, our light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
5... exd5 6. Bg5
{ The most principled move, pinning our knight.   6.Qc2  transposes to 5. Qc2. }
6... h6
{ A useful move. If the bishop retreats to h4 we'll have the option to push g5. }
7. Bh4 { White keeps the bishop and the pressure. } 7... Nbd7
{ This is my main recommendation. The idea is to play ...g5 next and then ...Ne4. If White forces us to take on g3, the d7-knight will be useful because it can go to either f6 or b6, and we won't be lagging much in development. }
8. Nd2
{ An interesting attempt. White prevents ...Ne4 at the expense of a tempo. }
8... c6
{ Secures the d5-pawn and also defends against potential Qa4+ tricks. Now we get a Carlsbad structure. Actually, most of the games continued with  8...Be7  followed by ...O-O, ...c5, ...b6 and ...Bb7 with a QGD structure. I think my suggestion is more interesting. }
9. e3 Nf8
{ It makes sense to bring the knight to g6 before castling. However, it's also possible to continue  9...O-O  ,  then ...Re8 and ...Nf8-g6. }
10. Bd3 Ng6 { We're forcing the white bishop out of the annoying pin. } 11. Bg3
O-O 12. Qc2 { White is targeting the g6-knight. } 12... Nh5
{ This is an important detail. We're sacrificing a pawn but get rid of both white bishops. }
13. Bxg6 { White accepts the offer. } 13... fxg6 14. Qxg6 Nxg3
{ Continuing as planned. } 15. hxg3
{ This is useful in order to activate the rook. } 15... Bf5
{ Comes with tempo. } 16. Qh5 Qd7
{ Followed by ...Rae8 and possibly ...Bd6 to prevent Nf3-e5. Black enjoys active play here. }
*

