14... Qf6
{ Hitting the f2-pawn and preparing ...Bf5. Of course  15.Nb5  is not dangerous because of ...O-O. }
15. Nb3 { Defends f2. } 15... Bf5
{ Thus we'll trade the bishops. It was also possible to do without this and continue with  15...O-O  and then ...c6 and so on. }
16. Bd3 Bxd3 17. Rxd3 O-O
{ The position is about equal. Our king is safe. White can play g4 and then try to bring a knight to f5, but it's not so easy and we'll be able to exchange it with ...Ne7 or ...Nd6. Black had no problems in the correspondence game Langer, R 2455 - Yunusov, A 2455 ICCF 2019. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 5.cxd5 exd5 6.Bg5 h6 7.Bh4 − 7...Nbd7 Main Line"]
[Black "7.Bh4 Nbd7 8.Qc2 with 9.Bg3 & 13.O-O-O #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5
{ A principled move, and one of the main lines. White aims for a harmonious development by either Bg5 or Bf4 followed by e3, Bd3. On the other hand, our light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
5... exd5 6. Bg5
{ The most principled move, pinning our knight.   6.Qc2  transposes to 5. Qc2. }
6... h6
{ A useful move. If the bishop retreats to h4 we'll have the option to push g5. }
7. Bh4 { White keeps the bishop and the pressure. } 7... Nbd7
{ This is my main recommendation. The idea is to play ...g5 next and then ...Ne4. If White forces us to take on g3, the d7-knight will be useful because it can go to either f6 or b6, and we won't be lagging much in development. }
8. Qc2
{ A flexible move. White is defending the knight in advance and only then is going to develop with e3 and Bd3. }
8... g5
{ We continue our plan of grabbing the dark-squared bishop. The other main move is ...c5, but that's a different setup than the one I'm recommending. }
9. Bg3 Ne4
{ That was the point. If White doesn't challenge our central knight quickly, we're going to push ...h5-h4 to harass the g3-bishop. }
10. Nd2 { A typical reply - White gets rid of our central knight. } 10... Nxg3
{ We need to exchange the dark-squared bishop. } 11. hxg3 Nb6
{ Thus Black is better prepared against e4.  11...c6  transposes to the line with 7... g5.   12.e3  also transposes. }
12. a3 { This makes sense. Depending on our reply White can continue with e4. }
12... Bf8 { The best place for the bishop in case White goes for e4. } 13.
O-O-O
{ White intends to go e4 on the next move and open up the center. We have to act carefully. }
13... Bg7 { We are ready to evacuate the king to the kingside in case of e4. }
14. e4 { White opens up the center. } 14... dxe4
{ We're in time for this exchange. We'll be able to complete development afterwards. }
15. Ncxe4 { Looks a bit strange. The idea is to bring the other knight to f3. }
15... O-O { We bring the king to safety and prepare ...Re8. } 16. Nf3
{ Threatening Nexg5. } 16... Re8
{ We completed development and can continue with ...Bf5 and ...c6. Our king is safe due to the g7-bishop. }
