[Black "7.Bh4 Nbd7 8.Rc1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5
{ A principled move, and one of the main lines. White aims for a harmonious development by either Bg5 or Bf4 followed by e3, Bd3. On the other hand, our light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
5... exd5 6. Bg5
{ The most principled move, pinning our knight.   6.Qc2  transposes to 5. Qc2. }
6... h6
{ A useful move. If the bishop retreats to h4 we'll have the option to push g5. }
7. Bh4 { White keeps the bishop and the pressure. } 7... Nbd7
{ This is my main recommendation. The idea is to play ...g5 next and then ...Ne4. If White forces us to take on g3, the d7-knight will be useful because it can go to either f6 or b6, and we won't be lagging much in development. }
8. Rc1 { A prophylactic move - White defends the c3-knight in advance. } 8...
g5 { Our typical plan works. } 9. Bg3 Ne4
{ ...h5 is a threat if White is not fast enough in challenging our central knight. }
10. Qb3 Bxc3+ { We have to go for this - d5 was attacked as well. } 11. bxc3 c6
{ A safe continuation, defending the d5-pawn. We are threatening ...h5, and the d7-knight controls the important e5-square.  11...Nb6  is possible but very risky  12.e3  h5  and we already start playing against the dark-squared bishop.It transposes to the chapter on 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4, into the     5.cxd5  exd5  6.Bf4  Ne4  7.Rc1  Nd7  8.Qb3  Bxc3+  9.bxc3  Nb6  10.e3  g5  11.Bg3  h5  line. }
12. Nd2 { White has to fight against the e4-knight. } 12... Ndf6
{ We're supporting the e4-knight. } 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. e3 Qe7
{ A useful move defending the b7-pawn so that we can play ...Be6. We are also ready to go ...h5. The position is about equal. A sample line goes  15.Bd3  h5  16.c4  Nxg3  17.hxg3  Be6  . }
