[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5
{ A principled move, and one of the main lines. White aims for a harmonious development by either Bg5 or Bf4 followed by e3, Bd3. On the other hand, our light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
5... exd5 6. Bg5
{ The most principled move, pinning our knight.   6.Qc2  transposes to 5. Qc2. }
6... h6
{ A useful move. If the bishop retreats to h4 we'll have the option to push g5. }
7. Bh4 { White keeps the bishop and the pressure. } 7... Nbd7
{ This is my main recommendation. The idea is to play ...g5 next and then ...Ne4. If White forces us to take on g3, the d7-knight will be useful because it can go to either f6 or b6, and we won't be lagging much in development. }
8. e3 { The move seen most often in practice. } 8... g5 9. Bg3 Ne4
{ This is the point of the previous move. If White doesn't do anything about our knight, we're going to go after the white bishop with ...h5 and ...h4. }
10. Nd2 { White wants to get rid of our central knight. } 10... Nxg3
{ It's important to get rid of the bishop. It's just wrong to try and win a pawn by  10...Nxc3?  11.bxc3  Bxc3  because after  12.Rc1  the position opens up and we're lagging in development. }
11. hxg3 Nb6
{ The knight is well placed here. Given time we can consolidate the position by means of ...Be6 and ...c6. }
12. Qb3 { White has a lead in development and is trying to act fast. } 12...
Be7
{ It's a matter of taste where to retreat the bishop. On d6 it was not so good because of e4, but  12...Bf8!?  is quite possible. Then we can consider ...Bg7 and ...O-O in some cases. With the text we can claim that the bishop has already been developed. Our follow-up is ...Be6, ...Qd7 and ...O-O-O. }
13. Bd3 Be6
{ This is more fun to play in connection with our next move.  13...c6  is safer and also good. We can play ...Be6 afterwards, but if White goes  14.f4  there is  14...Bg4  in one move. }
14. f4 { A good attempt to fight for an advantage. } 14... c5
{ Here is the surprise move! It turns out it's quite possible to go for this push. }
15. dxc5 { Leads to a forced line. } 15... d4 { The only move. } 16. Qb5+ Bd7
17. c6 { The only way to save the piece. } 17... Bxc6 { Again the only move. }
18. Qe5 f6 19. Qe6 Qc8
{ After the trade of queens Black has a good endgame. In the long term, we can try to make use of the bishop pair. }
*

