[Round "?"]
[White "2) 6.Bg5 h6 7.Bh4 − 7...g5 Alternative"]
[Black "7.Bh4 g5 8.Bg3 with 9.Nd2 & 11.Qc2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5
{ A principled move, and one of the main lines. White aims for a harmonious development by either Bg5 or Bf4 followed by e3, Bd3. On the other hand, our light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
5... exd5 6. Bg5
{ The most principled move, pinning our knight.   6.Qc2  transposes to 5. Qc2. }
6... h6
{ A useful move. If the bishop retreats to h4 we'll have the option to push g5. }
7. Bh4 { White keeps the bishop and the pressure. } 7... g5
{ This is the direct approach. We act quickly and the plan is to remove the pin, get the knight to e4, and take the dark-squared bishop. I used to play this line when I started playing Ragozin as Black. I think it works, but nowadays I prefer to prepare ...g5 by going ...Nbd7 first. }
8. Bg3 Ne4 { This was the plan of the previous move. } 9. Nd2
{ This is the best. White wants to get rid of the e4-knight and forces us to take a decision. }
9... Nxg3
{ We need to take the bishop, definitely! After  9...Nxc3  10.bxc3  Bxc3  11.Rc1  Ba5  12.e3  White gets tremendous compensation, and his position is easy to play. }
10. hxg3 c6
{ A logical, consolidating move. We defend the d5-pawn and prepare ...Nd7. }
11. Qc2 { A flexible move which prepares e4 in one go. } 11... Nd7
{ A flexible move - the knight goes either to f6 or b6. Once we finish development we'll get a strategically good position, but now White is to move and he can directly play e4, or first include a3. }
12. a3 { White is asking us a question about the bishop. } 12... Be7
{ It looks best to retreat the bishop here. It allows us to get the king to g7 via f8. Thus we are better prepared against e4 with the inclusion of Qc2 and ...Nd7.   12...Bf8  is a bit slow with the knight on d7, because after e4 we have to waste another tempo on ...Nb6. White has an initiative after  13.e4  dxe4  14.Ncxe4!?  in order to bring the other knight to f3.  14...Nb6  in order to prevent Nd6+  15.O-O-O  Bg7  16.Bd3  . }
13. e3 { This is too slow, allowing us to harmoniously complete development. }
13... Nb6 { Also possible was to bring the king to g7 by  13...Kf8  . } 14. Bd3
Be6 { With a solid position. We can go ...Qd7 and ...O-O-O next. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) 6.Bg5 h6 7.Bh4 − 7...g5 Alternative"]
[Black "7.Bh4 g5 8.Bg3 with 9.Nd2 & 11.Qc2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5
{ A principled move, and one of the main lines. White aims for a harmonious development by either Bg5 or Bf4 followed by e3, Bd3. On the other hand, our light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
5... exd5 6. Bg5
{ The most principled move, pinning our knight.   6.Qc2  transposes to 5. Qc2. }
6... h6
{ A useful move. If the bishop retreats to h4 we'll have the option to push g5. }
7. Bh4 { White keeps the bishop and the pressure. } 7... g5
{ This is the direct approach. We act quickly and the plan is to remove the pin, get the knight to e4, and take the dark-squared bishop. I used to play this line when I started playing Ragozin as Black. I think it works, but nowadays I prefer to prepare ...g5 by going ...Nbd7 first. }
8. Bg3 Ne4 { This was the plan of the previous move. } 9. Nd2
{ This is the best. White wants to get rid of the e4-knight and forces us to take a decision. }
9... Nxg3
{ We need to take the bishop, definitely! After  9...Nxc3  10.bxc3  Bxc3  11.Rc1  Ba5  12.e3  White gets tremendous compensation, and his position is easy to play. }
10. hxg3 c6
{ A logical, consolidating move. We defend the d5-pawn and prepare ...Nd7. }
11. Qc2 { A flexible move which prepares e4 in one go. } 11... Nd7
{ A flexible move - the knight goes either to f6 or b6. Once we finish development we'll get a strategically good position, but now White is to move and he can directly play e4, or first include a3. }
12. a3 { White is asking us a question about the bishop. } 12... Be7
{ It looks best to retreat the bishop here. It allows us to get the king to g7 via f8. Thus we are better prepared against e4 with the inclusion of Qc2 and ...Nd7.   12...Bf8  is a bit slow with the knight on d7, because after e4 we have to waste another tempo on ...Nb6. White has an initiative after  13.e4  dxe4  14.Ncxe4!?  in order to bring the other knight to f3.  14...Nb6  in order to prevent Nd6+  15.O-O-O  Bg7  16.Bd3  . }
13. e4 { A good try to fight for an advantage - White is ready for this push. }
13... dxe4
{ I think it's good to clear the center. The idea is to bring the king to g7 via f8, and go ...Nb6 to stop d5. This was not seen often in practice, but I think it deserves attention.In some correspondence games Black preferred  13...Nb6  followed by ...Be6. That is also possible, but it gives White the option to push e5, gaining some space. }
14. O-O-O { White can postpone taking on e4 - the pawn is going nowhere. }
14... Kf8 { The king goes to safety as soon as possible. } 15. Ncxe4 Kg7
{ d5 is not a threat yet, and we're planning ...Nf6 the g5-pawn is defended now. }
16. Nc4 Nf6 { It's good if we manage to trade the knights. } 17. Nc5 Nd5
{ The position is really unclear. The white king is a bit safer than ours, but not by much - there are always ideas to push ...b5-b4. The dark-squared bishop protects our king.We should be careful about the f5-square - if White manages to trade our light-squared bishop and put a knight there we're in trouble. However, this doesn't seem likely.   The correspondence game Buchan, A 2369 - LeBled, P 2369 ICCF 2022 continued  18.Kb1  Bf6  19.Ne5  Qc7  20.Re1  b6  21.Nb3  Be6  22.Bc4  c5  23.f4  Rad8  and eventually ended in a draw. }
