[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5
{ A principled move, and one of the main lines. White aims for a harmonious development by either Bg5 or Bf4 followed by e3, Bd3. On the other hand, our light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
5... exd5 6. Bg5
{ The most principled move, pinning our knight.   6.Qc2  transposes to 5. Qc2. }
6... h6
{ A useful move. If the bishop retreats to h4 we'll have the option to push g5. }
7. Bxf6 { White goes for a simple play. } 7... Qxf6 8. e3
{ Allows Black to get easy play. } 8... c6
{ This defends the d5-pawn in advance and now we'll be able to keep the dark-squared bishop. }
9. Bd3 { White intends to castle and then play e4 at the right moment. } 9...
O-O 10. O-O Nd7 { Prevents Ne5. } 11. a3 Bd6
{ We keep the bishop. We're preparing to retreat the queen to e7 and then bring the knight to f6. }
12. e4
{ Sooner or later White has to go for this, and now it comes with tempo. }
12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Qe7 14. Re1 Nf6 { According to the plan. } 15. Nxd6 Qxd6
{ The position is about equal. We have good control over the d5-square and in the long run we can play against the isolated pawn. }
