{ This line is quite fashionable, and I also used it successfully a few times. White wants to develop the pieces with e3, Bd3 and O-O without having to deal with ...h6-g5 like in the Bg5 lines.I decided to give 2 alternatives for Black here because Bf4 is quite fashionable nowadays. Both lines are sound and may have a surprise effect on your opponent! }
6... Ne4 7. Rc1 { Defends the knight. } 7... Nd7
{ An interesting idea. The knight is more flexible here than on c6 and can go to b6.  7...Nc6  is the most played move, but let's surprise our opponent! }
8. e3 { A natural developing move that doesn't take into account our ideas. }
8... g5 { Whenever possible we go chasing this bishop. } 9. Be5
{ It's not easy to understand why this is better than Bg3. The point is that after  9...f6  10.Bg3  h5  11.h4  White is better due to the misplaced pawn on f6. }
9... O-O
{ Now the white bishop has no scope and we can take it at the right moment. }
10. Bd3 Bxc3+ { It's useful to include this first. } 11. bxc3 g4
{ The idea is to dislodge the white knight and then take on e5. } 12. Rg1
{ An original attempt to keep the knight on f3. } 12... Nxe5
{ This is good now because White cannot castle anymore and the rook on g1 looks misplaced. }
13. Nxe5 Qh4
{ With a playable position for both sides. We can drive the white knight back with ...f6 at the right moment. }
*

