[Round "?"]
[White "4) 6.Bf4"]
[Black "6.Bf4 Ne4 7.Rc1 #9 (Alternative)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5
{ A principled move, and one of the main lines. White aims for a harmonious development by either Bg5 or Bf4 followed by e3, Bd3. On the other hand, our light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
5... exd5 6. Bf4
{ This line is quite fashionable, and I also used it successfully a few times. White wants to develop the pieces with e3, Bd3 and O-O without having to deal with ...h6-g5 like in the Bg5 lines.I decided to give 2 alternatives for Black here because Bf4 is quite fashionable nowadays. Both lines are sound and may have a surprise effect on your opponent! }
6... Ne4 7. Rc1 { Defends the knight. } 7... Nd7
{ An interesting idea. The knight is more flexible here than on c6 and can go to b6.  7...Nc6  is the most played move, but let's surprise our opponent! }
8. Qb3 { A logical reply, although it hasn't been played so far. } 8... Bxc3+
9. bxc3 Nb6
{ The knight is doing a good job here - defending b7, d5 and also controlling the important c4-square. A direct threat is ...g5, harassing the white bishop. Another plan is ...O-O followed by ...Re8, ...Bf5 and ...c5 at the right moment. }
10. e3 { Normal development, but it doesn't take our threats into account. }
10... g5
{ It's principled to chase the bishop, but it leads to huge complications. Go for this only if you're ready to take some risks. }
11. Bg3 h5
{ With counterplay against the bishop. We can reach this position also from the move order   5.cxd5  exd5  6.Bg5  h6  7.Bh4  Nbd7  8.Rc1  g5  9.Bg3  Ne4  10.Qb3  Bxc3+  11.bxc3  Nb6  . }
12. c4
{ The most ambitious reply. If  12.h4  White allows the doubled pawns after  12...Nxg3  . }
12... h4 { There is no turning back - we are going after the bishop. } 13. Be5
{ It's much better for White to give up the bishop on e5. } 13... f6
{ The bishop is finally trapped. } 14. cxd5
{ White takes control over the center, opens the c-file, and prepares Bb5+.  14.c5  can be met with  14...Nc4  15.Rxc4  dxc4  16.Bxc4  g4  with an unbalanced position where Black is doing fine. }
14... fxe5 { Gaining the piece justifies Black's strategy. } 15. Bb5+
{ Was played in Duda, J 2731 - Giri, A 2764 chess24.com INT 2022. }
15... Bd7
{ The position is extremely sharp, and this seems to be more accurate than  15...Kf8  , which has been tried before. }
16. Nxe5 Nd6
{ With a completely unbalanced position. White has enough compensation for the piece but nothing more. The black king will not find some safe shelter and will probably have to stay in the center. For the moment, the b5-bishop is attacked, and depending on what White does, some possible ideas are ...h3 or ...Qf6. }
