{ A principled move, and one of the main lines. White aims for a harmonious development by either Bg5 or Bf4 followed by e3, Bd3. On the other hand, our light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
5... exd5 6. Bf4
{ This line is quite fashionable, and I also used it successfully a few times. White wants to develop the pieces with e3, Bd3 and O-O without having to deal with ...h6-g5 like in the Bg5 lines.I decided to give 2 alternatives for Black here because Bf4 is quite fashionable nowadays. Both lines are sound and may have a surprise effect on your opponent! }
6... O-O
{ I give this as an alternative to ...Ne4 followed by ...Nd7. Our idea is to break the center with ...c5. }
7. e3 c5 { A principled break in the center. } 8. Be2 { Looks a bit passive. }
8... c4
{ It's nice to grab some space. Besides the white bishop was better on c2 than e2. }
9. Qc2 { Prevents ...Bf5. If  9.O-O  we can go  9...Bf5  and then ...Nc6. }
9... Nc6 10. O-O Ne7
{ The bishop will get to f5 anyway. I can already see Black fighting for an advantage here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) 6.Bf4"]
[Black "6.Bf4 O-O 7.e3 #4 (Alternative)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5
{ A principled move, and one of the main lines. White aims for a harmonious development by either Bg5 or Bf4 followed by e3, Bd3. On the other hand, our light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
5... exd5 6. Bf4
{ This line is quite fashionable, and I also used it successfully a few times. White wants to develop the pieces with e3, Bd3 and O-O without having to deal with ...h6-g5 like in the Bg5 lines.I decided to give 2 alternatives for Black here because Bf4 is quite fashionable nowadays. Both lines are sound and may have a surprise effect on your opponent! }
6... O-O
{ I give this as an alternative to ...Ne4 followed by ...Nd7. Our idea is to break the center with ...c5. }
7. e3 c5 { A principled break in the center. } 8. dxc5 Qa5
{ Here we need to show some accuracy. This is good because we can meet  9.Rc1  with  9...Qxa2  . }
9. Nd2 { Covers the pin and intends either Rc1 or Nb3. } 9... Nc6
{ This is interesting because we have the strong threat of ...d4, opening up the white king.  9...Bxc3  10.bxc3  Qxc5  is a sound alternative. }
10. Nb3
{ The logical follow-up.  10.Bd6?  would be a mistake in view of  ...d4!  with a winning position. }
10... Bxc3+ { Forced. } 11. bxc3 Qxc3+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2
{ So far we followed an online game between Carlsen and Aronian. } 13... d4
{ Aronian continued with ...Ne4+ followed by ...g5 which was good enough. However, this is a more direct way to play the position. }
14. Nxd4 Rd8
{ We're going to take back the pawn. The position is about equal. White has the bishop pair, but his king is exposed and the c5-pawn can sometimes become a target. }
