[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5
{ A principled move, and one of the main lines. White aims for a harmonious development by either Bg5 or Bf4 followed by e3, Bd3. On the other hand, our light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
5... exd5 6. Bf4
{ This line is quite fashionable, and I also used it successfully a few times. White wants to develop the pieces with e3, Bd3 and O-O without having to deal with ...h6-g5 like in the Bg5 lines.I decided to give 2 alternatives for Black here because Bf4 is quite fashionable nowadays. Both lines are sound and may have a surprise effect on your opponent! }
6... O-O
{ I give this as an alternative to ...Ne4 followed by ...Nd7. Our idea is to break the center with ...c5. }
7. e3 c5 { A principled break in the center. } 8. dxc5 Qa5
{ Here we need to show some accuracy. This is good because we can meet  9.Rc1  with  9...Qxa2  . }
9. Be5 Nfd7
{ True, the knight could have jumped to e4, but here it looks more interesting to me. }
10. Bd6 Rd8
{ An important detail. The rook will defend the d5-pawn in some lines. } 11.
Rc1 Nxc5 { We need to get rid of this pawn to untangle our pieces. } 12. Be7
{ An attempt to discoordinate our pieces. Note that  12.Bxc5  is well met by  12...Bxc5  when the d5-pawn is defended. }
12... Nd3+ { It's just a trade. } 13. Bxd3 Bxe7 14. O-O Nc6
{ The bishop pair fully compensates for the isolated pawn. } 15. h3 Bf6
{ The bishop is active here, and if White goes for Na4 we can regroup with ...Rd6 and ...Qd8, for example,  16.a3  g6  a useful move  17.Na4  Rd6  18.b4  Qd8  . }
