[White "5) 5.Qa4+ Nc6 6.e3"]
[Black "7.Qc2 dxc4 8.Bxc4 with 9.O-O #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+
{ This check is one of the main lines in the Ragozin. White forces us to play ...Nc6 and claims the knight is slightly misplaced there - it's not so easy to push ...c5, but ...dxc4 and ...e5 becomes a viable idea. The white queen usually goes back later on. }
5... Nc6 6. e3 O-O 7. Qc2
{ The queen did its job to lure the knight to c6 and now returns to a better square. }
7... dxc4
{ This is my main suggestion, a move I already played several times. The point is to clear out the center by playing ...Bd6 and ...e5 we cannot play ...Bd6 immediately because White goes c5.   7...Re8  is played often here I even tried it once. However, I think Black needs to be precise there. The move I recommend is more clear cut. }
8. Bxc4 Bd6 { A necessary regrouping in order to prepare ...e5. } 9. O-O e5 10.
h3 { Prevents ...Bg4. } 10... a6
{ A useful move, the point is to control b5 and sometimes even go for it. I went for this in the first game where I faced this variation. Later I switched to  10...Bd7  . While preparing this course I analyzed the position thoroughly and now I prefer the text. }
11. a3 { A useful move, too. In case of ...b5 the bishop can go to a2. } 11...
h6
{ After the exchange on d4 there is no Bg5, and also we can play ...Re8 without fearing Ng5. }
12. Rd1 { A principled reply. } 12... Bd7 { Addresses the pin on the d-file. }
13. Nh4 { The knight is looking for opportunities on the light squares. } 13...
exd4 { It looks like a good moment to open up the center. } 14. exd4 b5
{ We're starting our counterplay on the queenside. It was also possible to go for simplifications with  14...Nd5  the h4-knight is hanging. }
15. Bb3 Na5 16. Ba2 Nc4
{ We've just managed to neutralize the light-squared bishop. The position is playable for both sides. ...Re8 is a move we want to make next. }
*

