Qxc3 Rd8 { We're preparing ...e5. } 10. b4 e5
{ Yes, this works, even though the pawn is not defended. } 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12.
dxe5 Ne4
{ This is the point. It all works because White is lagging in development. }
13. Qc2
{ A natural square for the queen. If White plays  13.Qb2  to keep the e5-pawn defended then we can play  13...dxc4  14.Bxc4  Qg5  15.O-O  Bh3  16.f4  Qg6  with a nice position and good compensation for the pawn - for instance ...Rd2 is a threat. }
13... Bf5 { Looks tempting.  13...a5!?  deserves attention as well. } 14. Bd3
Qxe5 { We finally take the pawn back. } 15. Bb2 Qe6
{ The position is about equal. The active pieces compensate for the bishop pair. }
