[White "5) 5.Qa4+ Nc6 6.e3"]
[Black "7.Qc2 Qe7 8.Bd2 #1 (Alternative)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+
{ This check is one of the main lines in the Ragozin. White forces us to play ...Nc6 and claims the knight is slightly misplaced there - it's not so easy to push ...c5, but ...dxc4 and ...e5 becomes a viable idea. The white queen usually goes back later on. }
5... Nc6 6. e3 O-O 7. Qc2
{ The queen did its job to lure the knight to c6 and now returns to a better square. }
7... Qe7
{ I offer this as an alternative. It's a new idea, played in just a few games so far. The position may become sharp soon. The idea is to prepare ...e5, either immediately or after ...dxc4. }
8. Bd2
{ This was seen most often so far and it makes sense because it fights against ...e5. Given time, White wants to go a3 and take our bishop. }
8... dxc4 { We start acting in the center immediately. } 9. Bxc4 e5
{ This is the point. } 10. O-O { Safe play. } 10... exd4
{ We're doing fine once we clear the center. } 11. Nxd4
{ If  11.exd4  Bg4  is unpleasant. } 11... Nxd4 12. exd4 c6 13. Bf4
{ Activates the bishop and takes away the d6-square for our queen. We can meet the pin  13.Bg5  with  13...Qd6  . }
13... Re8
{ It makes sense to prevent Rfe1/Rae1. Black is fine here. The game Schandorff, L 2475 - Ochsner, B 2506 Svendborg 2022 continued with  13...Bg4  which allowed White to take control of the e-file. Even then the position was about equal. }
*

