{ King safety first. } 13... Bf5 { The start of a forced sequence. } 14. Bxb4
Qxb4 15. Qxe5 Qxc4 16. Qxe7 Rfe8
{ After the queen goes away the c7-pawn will not be hanging anymore. } 17. Qa3
Qxd5 { Finally, we got our pawn back. } 18. Rfd1 Qe4
{ I don't think Black can have problems here. The knight is not better than the bishop here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 5.Qa4+ Nc6 6.e3"]
[Black "7.Qc2 Qe7 8.Bd2 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+
{ This check is one of the main lines in the Ragozin. White forces us to play ...Nc6 and claims the knight is slightly misplaced there - it's not so easy to push ...c5, but ...dxc4 and ...e5 becomes a viable idea. The white queen usually goes back later on. }
5... Nc6 6. e3 O-O 7. Qc2
{ The queen did its job to lure the knight to c6 and now returns to a better square. }
7... Qe7
{ I offer this as an alternative. It's a new idea, played in just a few games so far. The position may become sharp soon. The idea is to prepare ...e5, either immediately or after ...dxc4. }
8. Bd2
{ This was seen most often so far and it makes sense because it fights against ...e5. Given time, White wants to go a3 and take our bishop. }
8... dxc4 { We start acting in the center immediately. } 9. Bxc4 e5
{ This is the point. } 10. d5
{ The principled move. White keeps the tension in the center. } 10... Qc5
{ Now the game becomes sharp. Retreating the knight was likely playing into White's hands. }
11. Ne4 { Looks logical and ambitious. } 11... Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Ne7 13. Nxe5
{ Too greedy. } 13... Bf5 14. Qf4 Bxd2+ 15. Kxd2
{ Until here we followed Keymer, V 2664 - Aronian, L 2772 Berlin 2022. }
15... g6
{ Not an easy move to find. We defend the bishop so that we can take on d5. A sample line goes  16.e4  how else to defend d5?  16...Qd4+  17.Ke2  Qxe4+  18.Qxe4  Bxe4  19.Nd7  Bxg2  20.Nxf8  Bxh1  21.Nxg6  hxg6  22.Rxh1  Re8  with a better ending for Black. White's structure looks bad. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 5.Qa4+ Nc6 6.e3"]
[Black "7.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+
{ This check is one of the main lines in the Ragozin. White forces us to play ...Nc6 and claims the knight is slightly misplaced there - it's not so easy to push ...c5, but ...dxc4 and ...e5 becomes a viable idea. The white queen usually goes back later on. }
5... Nc6 6. e3 O-O 7. a3 Bxc3+
{ We have to go for this, there is no point in retreating the bishop. } 8. bxc3
Bd7 9. Qc2
{ The queen has to retreat. Note that after  9.cxd5  there is  9...Ne5!  followed by ...Nxf3+ and only then ...exd5. }
9... Na5 { Forces White to take on d5. } 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Bd3 Re8
{ A useful move. We're going to push ...c5 next. } 12. a4
{ In order to activate the bishop via a3 and stop ...c5.  12.O-O  c5  looks good for Black. And also after   12.Ne5  we can play  12...c5  . }
12... c5 { We go for it nevertheless. } 13. dxc5 Qc7
{ Also possible is  13...Rc8  14.Ba3  Ne4  15.O-O  Rc6!  the rook is going to to g6 with threats against the white king. Black has good compensation for the pawn. }
14. Ba3 { Otherwise, Black takes the pawn with good play. } 14... Nc4
{ A good moment to include the knight into play. } 15. O-O
{ If  15.Bxc4  dxc4  16.O-O  there is  16...Bc6  with many threats and good compensation for the pawn. }
15... Nxa3 16. Rxa3 Qxc5
{ With an equal position, which occurred in the blitz game Kramnik, V 2772 - Grischuk, A 2736 Moscow blitz 2009. }
*

