[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 5.Qa4+ Nc6 6.e3"]
[Black "7.Bd2 with 9.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+
{ This check is one of the main lines in the Ragozin. White forces us to play ...Nc6 and claims the knight is slightly misplaced there - it's not so easy to push ...c5, but ...dxc4 and ...e5 becomes a viable idea. The white queen usually goes back later on. }
5... Nc6 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd2 { A principled developing move, addressing the pin. }
7... dxc4
{ We want to retreat the bishop to d6 and play ...a6. Afterwards we go for ...e5. }
8. Bxc4 a6
{ I like to include this move in order to keep the option to push ...b5 at any time. A fine point of it is that it prevents Nb5. Afterwards, we will proceed with ...Bd6 and then either ...e5 or ...b5.   8...Bd6  is played most often here, and it can transpose to our lines if we go afterwards ...a6. }
9. O-O
{ We'll consider this move order where White wants to skip Qc2 and bring a rook quickly to d1. Other moves like  9.a3  or  9.Rd1  can be met with  9...Bd6  and will just transpose. }
9... Bd6
{ We're ready for ...e5. Note that ...b5 is not yet a threat, but White has to take it into account every time. }
10. h3
{ A prophylactic move. It's always good to prevent ...Bg4 or ...Ng4 after Black goes ...e5. }
10... e5
{ There is no point in delaying it. Still, a move like  10...Rb8  looks weird but it's playable. }
11. dxe5 { White is clearing the center. } 11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5
{ ...Bxh3 and ...b5 is already an idea. } 13. Qc2 b5
{ Here it's the right time to start our play on the queenside. Note that a quiet approach with  13...Qe7  is not advisable. White won a nice game in Praggnanandhaa, R 2624 - Laurent Paoli, P 2487 Reykjavik 2022 after  14.f4!  Bxc3  15.Bxc3  Qxe3+  16.Kh2  Qb6  17.Rf3! }
14. Bd3 Bb7 { I like the bishop on this diagonal. } 15. f4
{ Here is the start of a forced line. If White doesn't act quickly Black gets a great position. }
15... Bd6 { It's better to keep the bishop in this situation. } 16. e4
{ White has to advance the pawns. } 16... Bc5+ 17. Kh2 b4
{ An important detail. We need to misplace the knight before going ...Ng4+. }
18. Na4 Ng4+ { The typical counterplay. } 19. Kg3
{ The king is not in danger here. Not yet. } 19... Ne3 20. Bxe3 Bxe3
{ With the last moves, we managed to misplace some white pieces Kg3, Na4 and also minimized the strength of the e5 push. }
21. Rae1 Bd4 { A nice square for the bishop. } 22. e5 Kh8
{ One last move to remember. The position remains unclear, but Black is fine. We can follow up with ...c5. White will strive for an attack on the kingside, although his knight is on the rim. }
*

