[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 5.Qa4+ Nc6 6.e3"]
[Black "7.Bd2 with 9.Qc2 & 10.a3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+
{ This check is one of the main lines in the Ragozin. White forces us to play ...Nc6 and claims the knight is slightly misplaced there - it's not so easy to push ...c5, but ...dxc4 and ...e5 becomes a viable idea. The white queen usually goes back later on. }
5... Nc6 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd2 { A principled developing move, addressing the pin. }
7... dxc4
{ We want to retreat the bishop to d6 and play ...a6. Afterwards we go for ...e5. }
8. Bxc4 a6
{ I like to include this move in order to keep the option to push ...b5 at any time. A fine point of it is that it prevents Nb5. Afterwards, we will proceed with ...Bd6 and then either ...e5 or ...b5.   8...Bd6  is played most often here, and it can transpose to our lines if we go afterwards ...a6. }
9. Qc2
{ The most often played move. The queen did its job to lure our knight to c6 and now returns to a better spot. }
9... Bd6
{ We regrouped our bishop. Now besides the typical idea ...e5, there is also the more ambitious ...b5. }
10. a3 { White wants to retreat the bishop to d3, but first prevents ...Nb4. }
10... e5
{ We switch to the main idea. I think the inclusion of ...a6 and a3 slightly favours Black. For one thing, castling long is not so appealing for White because of the a3 hook, and also we always keep the option to go ...b5. }
11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5
{ In all the games from my database White went for this. } 12... Bxe5 13. f4
{ An attempt to get something out of the position. } 13... Bxc3
{ It's good to trade the bishop here.  13...Bd6  is not recommended because of  14.O-O-O  , and the bishop sac   13...Bxf4  looks more fun than sound. }
14. Bxc3 Ng4
{ An important move. Note that the position is concrete, every tempo counts. If White has time to castle and roll the e-pawn forward, he gets a big advantage. The conclusion is that we must act quickly!In my game against Nicholas Pert Pert, N 2546 - Parligras, M 2575 England 2022 I forgot the line and played  14...Re8?!  first. But then after  15.O-O  Ng4?!  White could have gotten a big advantage with  16.Rae1!  and if  16...Nxe3  then  17.Bxf7!  wins. }
15. Bd4 { Defends the e3-pawn and prepares O-O-O. } 15... c5
{ Another move that we need to remember. The point is to gain time and also to prevent White from castling long. }
16. Bxc5 Re8 17. O-O { The white king needs shelter. } 17... Nxe3
{ We take back the pawn. } 18. Bxe3 Rxe3
{ This line could be reached also without the inclusion of a3 and ...a6. But here I think it's good to have ideas to play ...b5 and have the pawn defended. The game looks completely equal but I've seen in practice players losing similar positions with Black so we need to stay focused. }
19. Qf2 Re8
{ It's best to retreat the rook here where it protects the 8th rank. } 20. Rad1
Qf6 21. Qd4 Qxd4+ 22. Rxd4 Be6
{ The position is equal and a draw was soon agreed in Tari, A 2588 - Leko, P 2679 Douglas 2017. }
*

