{ This check is one of the main lines in the Ragozin. White forces us to play ...Nc6 and claims the knight is slightly misplaced there - it's not so easy to push ...c5, but ...dxc4 and ...e5 becomes a viable idea. The white queen usually goes back later on. }
5... Nc6 6. a3
{ This move gained in popularity recently. White loses a tempo to take our bishop, and then tries to get his bishop out to f4 or g5. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Bd7
{ A typical developing move, forcing White to take on d5 due to the threat of ...Nxd4. The other main option for Black is  7...Ne4  ,  stopping Bg5. The line with 6. a3 is fashionable nowadays and only further practical tests will show which direction is best. }
8. Qc2
{ Sometimes White decides to sacrifice a pawn in order to get typical compensation. }
8... dxc4 { We accept the challenge and grab the pawn. } 9. e4
{ White has a nice center and bishop pair, and hopes to get the pawn back later. }
9... Na5
{ A multi-purpose move - it defends the c4-pawn, opens up the bishop, threatens ...Nb3, and there is also the idea of ...c5. }
10. Bg5 { The annoying pin. } 10... h6
{ It seems like a good idea to include this. However, it's also possible to go  10...Bc6  immediately. }
11. Bxf6
{ Was played in Niemann, H 2687 - Maghsoodloo, P 2701 Ankara 2022. }
11... Qxf6
{ We can keep the pawn structure intact, there is no need to take with the pawn. }
12. Ne5 b5 { I don't think White has enough compensation for the pawn. } *

