[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+
{ This check is one of the main lines in the Ragozin. White forces us to play ...Nc6 and claims the knight is slightly misplaced there - it's not so easy to push ...c5, but ...dxc4 and ...e5 becomes a viable idea. The white queen usually goes back later on. }
5... Nc6 6. a3
{ This move gained in popularity recently. White loses a tempo to take our bishop, and then tries to get his bishop out to f4 or g5. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Bd7
{ A typical developing move, forcing White to take on d5 due to the threat of ...Nxd4. The other main option for Black is  7...Ne4  ,  stopping Bg5. The line with 6. a3 is fashionable nowadays and only further practical tests will show which direction is best. }
8. cxd5 exd5
{ This pawns exchange helps us a bit because it opens up our bishop and the e-file for the rook. }
9. Bg5 { The annoying pin. } 9... h6
{ I like to include this, it keeps options for ...g5. } 10. Bh4 g5
{ I think Black should play actively here. ...Ne4 is next. Also playable is  10...O-O  11.e3  Re8  12.Qc2  g5  13.Bg3  Ne4  . }
11. Bg3 Ne4 12. Qb3 { A double attack. } 12... Bf5
{ An accurate reply. We activate the bishop and defend the d5-pawn. } 13. Qxb7
{ Otherwise there is no point in playing Qb3. } 13... Na5
{ The b-file opened in our favour. } 14. Qxc7
{ Grabbing a second pawn. More considerate was  14.Qb4  c6  15.Nd2  Nxg3  16.hxg3  Rb8  with obvious compensation for Black. }
14... O-O 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8 16. e3
{ 16.Bc7  , with a double attack against knight and rook, can be answered with  16...Nb3  17.Rb1  and  17...Rd7  or  17...Rdc8  . }
16... Rdc8
{ Black was much better and went on to win in the correspondence game Wister, F 2371 - Csiba, T 2370 ICCF 2021. }
