[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) 5.Qa4+ Nc6 − 6th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "5.Qa4+ with 6.a3 & 9.Qc2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+
{ This check is one of the main lines in the Ragozin. White forces us to play ...Nc6 and claims the knight is slightly misplaced there - it's not so easy to push ...c5, but ...dxc4 and ...e5 becomes a viable idea. The white queen usually goes back later on. }
5... Nc6 6. a3
{ This move gained in popularity recently. White loses a tempo to take our bishop, and then tries to get his bishop out to f4 or g5. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Bd7
{ A typical developing move, forcing White to take on d5 due to the threat of ...Nxd4. The other main option for Black is  7...Ne4  ,  stopping Bg5. The line with 6. a3 is fashionable nowadays and only further practical tests will show which direction is best. }
8. cxd5 exd5
{ This pawns exchange helps us a bit because it opens up our bishop and the e-file for the rook. }
9. Qc2 { The queen is safe here. White's plan is to go Bg5. } 9... Na5
{ We can postpone castling for now and prepare ...c5. Of course,  9...O-O  is possible and the main line goes  10.Bg5  h6  11.Bh4  Na5  12.Ne5  g5!  13.Bg3  c5  . }
10. Ne5
{ An obvious move - when one knight goes to the rim, the other takes the central position. There is a threat of Bg5 with an unpleasant pin. }
10... h6
{ We're losing a tempo but prevent Bg5. The alternative is the direct  10...c5  . }
11. Bf4 { It's principled to develop the bishop here. } 11... c5
{ We can already break the center. } 12. e3
{ White continues development.  12.dxc5  is not an issue because of  12...O-O  and afterward, we'll take the pawn back with ...Rc8. }
12... O-O 13. Bd3
{ The bishop is active here, but it can be attacked with ...c4. } 13... c4
{ An interesting move which forces the events a bit. It was also possible to play slower like  13...Be6  or  13...Rc8  . }
14. Nxd7
{ White exchanges this bishop while it's still possible. Otherwise, the bishop can go to e6 or a4 after ...Nb3. Retreating the bishop  14.Be2  is more passive, and Black can create some threats after  14...Nb3  15.Ra2  Ba4  with ...Ne4 or ...Qa5 to follow. }
14... cxd3
{ The start of a forced sequence of moves. We sacrifice a pawn but get good compensation in return. It was also possible to take back on d7, but then White is left with the bishop pair. }
15. Nxf6+ { Forced. } 15... Qxf6 16. Qxd3 Rac8
{ Black has good compensation for the pawn here. An idea is to just double the rooks on the c-file - ...Rc4 and ...Rfc8. Note that  17.Qb5  is met with  ...Qd8  ,  defending both the d5-pawn and the knight. }
*

