{ This check is one of the main lines in the Ragozin. White forces us to play ...Nc6 and claims the knight is slightly misplaced there - it's not so easy to push ...c5, but ...dxc4 and ...e5 becomes a viable idea. The white queen usually goes back later on. }
5... Nc6 6. a3
{ This move gained in popularity recently. White loses a tempo to take our bishop, and then tries to get his bishop out to f4 or g5. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Bd7
{ A typical developing move, forcing White to take on d5 due to the threat of ...Nxd4. The other main option for Black is  7...Ne4  ,  stopping Bg5. The line with 6. a3 is fashionable nowadays and only further practical tests will show which direction is best. }
8. cxd5 exd5
{ This pawns exchange helps us a bit because it opens up our bishop and the e-file for the rook. }
9. Qc2 { The queen is safe here. White's plan is to go Bg5. } 9... Na5
{ We can postpone castling for now and prepare ...c5. Of course,  9...O-O  is possible and the main line goes  10.Bg5  h6  11.Bh4  Na5  12.Ne5  g5!  13.Bg3  c5  . }
