[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+
{ This check is one of the main lines in the Ragozin. White forces us to play ...Nc6 and claims the knight is slightly misplaced there - it's not so easy to push ...c5, but ...dxc4 and ...e5 becomes a viable idea. The white queen usually goes back later on. }
5... Nc6 6. Ne5
{ I don't think this move is justified. White tries to create some threats early on but they can easily be parried. }
6... Bd7 { Very natural, simply addressing the pin. } 7. Nxc6 Bxc3+ { Forced. }
8. bxc3 Bxc6
{ White got the bishop pair but is lagging in development. Also, the c4-pawn may be hanging in some lines. }
9. Qa3 { Prevents ...O-O. } 9... dxc4 { Free pawn. } 10. f3
{ White tries to build up a strong center, shutting out our bishop. So far it was Cori Tello, D 2382 - Zawadzka, J 2407 Sitges 2021. }
10... Nd5
{ The knight switches to the other side to defend the c4-pawn and makes ...f5 possible. }
11. e4 Nb6
{ The extra pawn is defended. We are going to play ...f5 to undermine the white center. }
