{ This check is one of the main lines in the Ragozin. White forces us to play ...Nc6 and claims the knight is slightly misplaced there - it's not so easy to push ...c5, but ...dxc4 and ...e5 becomes a viable idea. The white queen usually goes back later on. }
5... Nc6 6. Bg5
{ An attempt to transpose to   5.Bg5  h6  6.Bxf6  Qxf6  7.Qa4+  Nc6  ,  when White avoided 5... dxc4. }
6... dxc4
{ White's move order allows us an interesting extra option. We take a pawn and we'll try to hang onto it.   6...h6  7.Bxf6  Qxf6  transposes to another chapter. }
7. e4 { A direct approach. White takes over the center, but weakens d4. } 7...
Bd7 8. Qc2 h6
{ An important move, getting rid of the pin. There is no  9.Bh4  because of  9...g5  10.Bg3  g4  and d4 falls. }
9. Be3 b5 { Of course we keep the pawn. } 10. Be2 a6 11. O-O O-O
{ Black is a healthy pawn up. Most importantly we managed to get rid of the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal. }
