[Black "6.Bh4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5
{ One of the main moves to fight against the Ragozin. The pin is principled, and by not taking on d5 Black's c8-bishop remains shut off. The downside is that the c4-pawn is hanging. }
5... h6
{ By far the most played move. If the bishop retreats to h4 then it's good to take on c4. In over the board games, I also tried  5...dxc4  , transposing to a Vienna. However, I decided against recommending that because some lines are too forced, and if you forget some detail it can be decisive. }
6. Bh4
{ At first I thought that this move is not so good for White, but then I saw that Magnus Carlsen played it at the Chennai Olympiad. His opponent continued with ...O-O and eventually lost the game. The point of the move is that White keeps the dark-squared bishop at the expense of sacrificing a pawn. }
6... dxc4 { We take the pawn, and we'll be able to keep it by means of ...b5. }
7. a3 { This forces us to part with the bishop } 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 b5
{ It makes sense to defend the c4-pawn in advance. Also possible was  8...Nbd7  with the idea to play either ...c5 or ...b5. }
9. a4 { Undermining our pawn chain. } 9... c6
{ The only move that keeps the pawn chain intact. } 10. Qb1
{ A good square for the queen. Later on, we have to be careful about developing the bishop to b7 because the pin on the b-file might allow tricks with Bxc4.  10.Nd2  to prepare e4 can be met with  10...Nbd7  11.e4  e5  with a good position for Black. }
10... a6 { We need to safeguard the b5-pawn. } 11. e3
{ Simple development.  11.e4?  would be wrong due to  11...Qa5  with threats on c3 and e4. }
11... Nbd7
{ We continue development.  11...O-O  is the same thing, but not  11...Bb7?  due to  12.Bxc4! }
12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O Qe8
{ Obviously, the idea is to unpin the knight and maybe prepare ...Nd5 and ...f5. Other plans were possible as well, like  13...Ra7  in order to play ...Bb7 or  13...Qc7  .   White has enough compensation for the pawn due to the dark-squared bishop and better control of the center. On the other hand, Black has no reason to complain about his position. The correspondence game Vujnovic, R - Block, B 2260 ICCF 2021 continued with  14.Rc1  Nd5  , just the plan I mentioned,  15.Bg3  f5  with compensation. }
*

