1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5
{ One of the main moves to fight against the Ragozin. The pin is principled, and by not taking on d5 Black's c8-bishop remains shut off. The downside is that the c4-pawn is hanging. }
5... h6
{ By far the most played move. If the bishop retreats to h4 then it's good to take on c4. In over the board games, I also tried  5...dxc4  , transposing to a Vienna. However, I decided against recommending that because some lines are too forced, and if you forget some detail it can be decisive. }
6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. a3
{ White forces the exchange of the dark-squared bishop. The idea is to go for a quick g4 if we castle too early. }
7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 c5
{ We're breaking the center right away. We should refrain from castling short for now because then White could unbalance the position with g4. }
9. e3 Nc6 { And again, we delay castling so as not to allow White to play g4. }
10. cxd5
{ White has to do something. If  10.Bd3  we can play  10...dxc4  and gain a tempo. }
10... exd5 11. Bb5 { An attempt to go for active play. } 11... O-O 12. O-O c4
{ It deserves attention to gain some space on the queenside. The bishop will go to f5, and then we can prepare to push ...b5. Black is doing fine. }
