[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) 5.Bg5 h6 − Introduction"]
[Black "7.Qb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5
{ One of the main moves to fight against the Ragozin. The pin is principled, and by not taking on d5 Black's c8-bishop remains shut off. The downside is that the c4-pawn is hanging. }
5... h6
{ By far the most played move. If the bishop retreats to h4 then it's good to take on c4. In over the board games, I also tried  5...dxc4  , transposing to a Vienna. However, I decided against recommending that because some lines are too forced, and if you forget some detail it can be decisive. }
6. Bxf6
{ White gives up the bishop and goes for a strategic approach. He has good control in the center, while we still have to find a way to develop the light-squared bishop. }
6... Qxf6 7. Qb3
{ A solid system, where White tries to play for a slight advantage. } 7... c5
{ We need to fight for the center. We may have to sacrifice a pawn to complete development, but Black is doing fine. }
8. cxd5
{ It makes sense to trade the pawns. Maybe White can delay this a bit with  8.e3  O-O  but then after  9.cxd5  exd5  it will transpose.   8.dxc5  is not so good because of  8...Bxc3+  . }
8... exd5 9. dxc5 Bxc3+
{ It seems a good moment to spoil White's structure, and see how he's going to take it back.  9...Na6  was also possible. }
10. bxc3 { It usually favours Black to keep the queens on the board. } 10...
O-O
{ We can continue with ...Be6 and ...Nd7 to take the c5-pawn. White may take the b7-pawn, but we'll have plenty of compensation due to the open b and c-files. }
11. Nd4
{ It frees up the queen from defending the c3-pawn. Obviously, the knight is nicely placed there, but it took another tempo. }
11... Be6 { We continue our plan. First, we have to defend the d5-pawn. } 12.
Qxb7 { The only way to try to fight for an advantage. } 12... Nd7
{ OK, we are 2 pawns down, but our pieces are active. } 13. g3 Nxc5
{ This looks logical to me, it also comes with tempo. } 14. Qb4
{ The queen must defend the c3-pawn, otherwise ...Ne4 just wins. } 14... Rfc8
{ The other rook may be useful on the b-file. Black's position looks promising here. A sample line goes  15.Bg2  a5!?  , to misplace the queen a bit,  16.Qa3  Ne4  17.Bxe4  dxe4  18.O-O  Bh3  with good compensation. }
