[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) 5.Bg5 h6 − Introduction"]
[Black "7.Qb3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5
{ One of the main moves to fight against the Ragozin. The pin is principled, and by not taking on d5 Black's c8-bishop remains shut off. The downside is that the c4-pawn is hanging. }
5... h6
{ By far the most played move. If the bishop retreats to h4 then it's good to take on c4. In over the board games, I also tried  5...dxc4  , transposing to a Vienna. However, I decided against recommending that because some lines are too forced, and if you forget some detail it can be decisive. }
6. Bxf6
{ White gives up the bishop and goes for a strategic approach. He has good control in the center, while we still have to find a way to develop the light-squared bishop. }
6... Qxf6 7. Qb3
{ A solid system, where White tries to play for a slight advantage. } 7... c5
{ We need to fight for the center. We may have to sacrifice a pawn to complete development, but Black is doing fine. }
8. cxd5
{ It makes sense to trade the pawns. Maybe White can delay this a bit with  8.e3  O-O  but then after  9.cxd5  exd5  it will transpose.   8.dxc5  is not so good because of  8...Bxc3+  . }
8... exd5 9. e3 { With the idea to go Bb5+ or to take on c5. } 9... O-O
{ This is the easiest solution - we want to avoid Bb5.  9...Nc6  can be met with  10.Bb5  and after  10...O-O  11.dxc5  d4!  12.Bxc6  dxc3  13.Qxb4  cxb2  14.Rb1  bxc6  15.O-O  I think White is slightly better, although the position is close to equal. }
10. dxc5
{ White grabs a pawn and hopes to get some positional advantage while we try to get it back. }
10... Bxc3+ { We spoil the pawn structure. } 11. Qxc3
{ It's good for White to trade the queens. } 11... Qxc3+ 12. bxc3 Nd7
{ This looks like a simple solution. Top GMs like Caruana, Ding, and Giri went for it. The alternative is  12...Be6  . }
13. Rd1 { White is acting fast before we take back the c5-pawn. } 13... Nf6
{ The latest trends show this is the best. It was also possible to sacrifice the d5-pawn by means of ...Nxc5. }
14. c4 { This can be testing, but we're fine if we know what we're doing. }
14... Be6
{ An accurate reply - it's important to know that Nd4 and Nxe6 is not dangerous. }
15. Nd4 Rfc8
{ Another important detail - the a8-rook may be useful on b8, as can be seen in the line  16.c6  bxc6  17.c5  Rab8! }
16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. cxd5 Nxd5
{ I prefer to have the knight in the center, but  17...exd5  was possible too. }
18. Rc1 { Temporarily defends the pawn. } 18... Rc7
{ Followed by ..Rac8. We take back the pawn with an equal endgame. A sample line goes  19.Bd3  Rac8  20.Kd2  Rxc5  21.Rxc5  Rxc5  22.Rb1  b6  . }
