{ It's good for White to trade the queens. } 11... Qxc3+ 12. bxc3 Nd7
{ This looks like a simple solution. Top GMs like Caruana, Ding, and Giri went for it. The alternative is  12...Be6  . }
13. Rd1 { White is acting fast before we take back the c5-pawn. } 13... Nf6
{ The latest trends show this is the best. It was also possible to sacrifice the d5-pawn by means of ...Nxc5. }
14. Nd4
{ This was played most often here. However, White is not able to keep the c5-pawn. }
14... Bd7 { Stopping c6 and preparing ...Rfc8. } 15. f3
{ A useful move - White wants to avoid any unpleasant knight jump to e4. The immediate  15.Nb3  leads to the same thing after  15...Rfc8! }
15... Rfc8
{ It is important that this rook goes here. We need the a8-rook to defend the b7-pawn if White plays Rb1. }
16. Nb3 { This defends the pawn for now. } 16... Ba4
{ We'll go ...Bxb3 and then ...Rxc5. The waiting move  16...Kf8  is also possible. }
17. Rd4 { The rook is active here. } 17... Bxb3 18. axb3 Rxc5
{ We managed to take back the pawn, d5 is safely defended, and we may put some pressure on c3. }
19. Kd2 Rac8 { Just activating the rook, but not really attacking c3. } 20. Bd3
{ In order to bring the other rook into play. } 20... a5
{ Gains some space on the queenside. Just don't play  20...Rxc3?  because of  21.Bc4  losing an exchange. }
21. Rc1 Kf8
{ With an equal game as in Swiercz, D 2647 - Caruana, F 2800 Riga 2021. Neither side can make progress.In a must win situation we can play this position until the end, or try to deviate early on, for example by sacrificing a pawn with   13...Nxc5  . }
