1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5
{ One of the main moves to fight against the Ragozin. The pin is principled, and by not taking on d5 Black's c8-bishop remains shut off. The downside is that the c4-pawn is hanging. }
5... h6
{ By far the most played move. If the bishop retreats to h4 then it's good to take on c4. In over the board games, I also tried  5...dxc4  , transposing to a Vienna. However, I decided against recommending that because some lines are too forced, and if you forget some detail it can be decisive. }
6. Bxf6
{ White gives up the bishop and goes for a strategic approach. He has good control in the center, while we still have to find a way to develop the light-squared bishop. }
6... Qxf6 7. Qa4+ { A typical check to force our knight to c6. } 7... Nc6
{ Forced. } 8. e3 { This was played the most often in practice. } 8... O-O
{ We bring the king to safety. } 9. Rc1
{ The rook obviously belongs here, and now after ...dxc4 White goes Bxc4 directly. }
9... Rd8
{ We can also pass the move by activating our rook. Previously  9...Qg6  was considered good, but White gets some play after  10.h4! }
10. cxd5
{ This basically takes away our option to play ...dxc4. On the other hand, the light-squared bishop has good perspectives now. }
10... exd5 11. Be2 Bf8
{ Regrouping the pieces. One of the fine points of having a rook on b8 is that we can keep the bishop. }
12. O-O Ne7 { It's tempting to reroute the knight to g6 or f5. } 13. b4 a6
{ To stop the b-pawn. } 14. Qb3
{ In order to continue pushing, or even to bring a knight to c5 via a4. } 14...
c6 { Now the knight is ready to go to f5. } 15. Na4
{ White aims to bring the knight to c5. Until here we followed the game Dubrovin, R 2221 - Fedoseev, V 2674 Jurmala 2015. If  15.a4  then  15...Nf5  16.b5  Be6  Black is ready for the opening of the position. }
15... Rb8
{ Here I like this prophylactic move. We're defending the b7-pawn in advance, at the same time parrying Nb6. We can follow up with ...Ng6 or ...Nf5 with a nice position. }
