{ One of the main moves to fight against the Ragozin. The pin is principled, and by not taking on d5 Black's c8-bishop remains shut off. The downside is that the c4-pawn is hanging. }
5... h6
{ By far the most played move. If the bishop retreats to h4 then it's good to take on c4. In over the board games, I also tried  5...dxc4  , transposing to a Vienna. However, I decided against recommending that because some lines are too forced, and if you forget some detail it can be decisive. }
6. Bxf6
{ White gives up the bishop and goes for a strategic approach. He has good control in the center, while we still have to find a way to develop the light-squared bishop. }
6... Qxf6 7. Qa4+ { A typical check to force our knight to c6. } 7... Nc6
{ Forced. } 8. e3 { This was played the most often in practice. } 8... O-O
{ We bring the king to safety. } 9. Rc1
{ The rook obviously belongs here, and now after ...dxc4 White goes Bxc4 directly. }
9... Rd8
{ We can also pass the move by activating our rook. Previously  9...Qg6  was considered good, but White gets some play after  10.h4! }
10. Be2 { White shouldn't delay development for too long. } 10... dxc4
{ This is the point. White will have to spend another tempo to take back the pawn. }
11. Qb5 { The point is to meet  11...Bd7  with  12.Qxc4  . } 11... Qe7
{ With the idea to have the bishop defended so that we can play ...Na5. The immediate  11...e5  was also possible. }
12. a3 Bxc3+
{ This forces the issue a bit. The plan is to follow up with ...e5 and open up the c8-bishop. It was possible to play  12...Bd6  as well. After  13.Qxc4  e5  14.d5  Nb8  followed by ...Nd7 a complicated position arises. }
13. Rxc3 e5 { This is important, as otherwise, Black is worse. } 14. d5
{ White was counting on this. } 14... e4
{ Only like this - retreating the knight was too passive. } 15. dxc6
{ Forced. } 15... exf3 16. Bxf3
{ 16.cxb7  loses to  16...Qd6  17.Bxf3  Qd2+  followed by 18. Bxb7. } 16... b6
{ The c6-pawn is not as strong as it looks because we have good control of the d-file. The position is unbalanced but about equal. We'll have enough compensation for the pawn due to the active pieces, and even the endgames are fine. A sample line goes  17.Qxc4  Be6  18.Qf4  Qd6  . }
*

