5... h6
{ By far the most played move. If the bishop retreats to h4 then it's good to take on c4. In over the board games, I also tried  5...dxc4  , transposing to a Vienna. However, I decided against recommending that because some lines are too forced, and if you forget some detail it can be decisive. }
6. Bxf6
{ White gives up the bishop and goes for a strategic approach. He has good control in the center, while we still have to find a way to develop the light-squared bishop. }
6... Qxf6 7. Qa4+ { A typical check to force our knight to c6. } 7... Nc6
{ Forced. } 8. e3 { This was played the most often in practice. } 8... O-O
{ We bring the king to safety. } 9. cxd5
{ White keeps the center closed, but this opens up perspectives for our light-squared bishop. }
9... exd5 10. Be2 Be6
{ We continue our development. I prefer this to  10...a6  , although it's about the same thing. }
11. O-O a6 12. Rfc1
{ This line reached some popularity after Magnus Carlsen used it to win against Aronian in 2015. White has a long-term plan - Qd1, a3-b4, Na4-c5. }
