[Black "7.Qa4+ with 8.e3 & 9.cxd5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5
{ One of the main moves to fight against the Ragozin. The pin is principled, and by not taking on d5 Black's c8-bishop remains shut off. The downside is that the c4-pawn is hanging. }
5... h6
{ By far the most played move. If the bishop retreats to h4 then it's good to take on c4. In over the board games, I also tried  5...dxc4  , transposing to a Vienna. However, I decided against recommending that because some lines are too forced, and if you forget some detail it can be decisive. }
6. Bxf6
{ White gives up the bishop and goes for a strategic approach. He has good control in the center, while we still have to find a way to develop the light-squared bishop. }
6... Qxf6 7. Qa4+ { A typical check to force our knight to c6. } 7... Nc6
{ Forced. } 8. e3 { This was played the most often in practice. } 8... O-O
{ We bring the king to safety. } 9. cxd5
{ White keeps the center closed, but this opens up perspectives for our light-squared bishop. }
9... exd5 10. Be2 Be6
{ We continue our development. I prefer this to  10...a6  , although it's about the same thing. }
11. O-O a6 12. Rfc1
{ This line reached some popularity after Magnus Carlsen used it to win against Aronian in 2015. White has a long-term plan - Qd1, a3-b4, Na4-c5. }
12... Bd6
{ However, later on, it was discovered that Black gets a good position by going for an attack on the kingside. It turns out that White's position can become dangerous. }
13. Qd1
{ White's best bet - there are 2 plans available - a3 and b4, or Na4-c5. }
13... Ne7 { Regrouping the pieces. } 14. Na4
{ The more ambitious plan- White wants to put the knight on c5 and push b4, saving the move a3. }
14... b6
{ Prevents Nc5. Of course, it was also possible to let the knight get there. However, it seems more to the point not to allow your opponent to realize his plans. }
15. b4 { The typical idea is to reroute the knight to d3 via b2. } 15... g5
{ We're getting our own counterplay. } 16. Nb2 a5
{ I like this idea of blocking the queenside.  16...Ng6  is played more often in practice. }
17. b5 { Forced. } 17... h5
{ Just pushing the pawns, and preparing regrouping with ...Qh6. } 18. Nd3 Qh6
{ I think Black is slightly better here. White has no counterplay and in the meantime we can slowly improve our position and push the pawns on the kingside.White can try to double the rooks on the c-file and sacrifice the exchange on c7, so we should defend c7 twice. The queen on h6 is useful because sometimes we can sacrifice the h-pawn and get an attack on the h-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) 5.Bg5 h6 − Introduction"]
[Black "7.Qa4+ with 8.e3 & 9.cxd5 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5
{ One of the main moves to fight against the Ragozin. The pin is principled, and by not taking on d5 Black's c8-bishop remains shut off. The downside is that the c4-pawn is hanging. }
5... h6
{ By far the most played move. If the bishop retreats to h4 then it's good to take on c4. In over the board games, I also tried  5...dxc4  , transposing to a Vienna. However, I decided against recommending that because some lines are too forced, and if you forget some detail it can be decisive. }
6. Bxf6
{ White gives up the bishop and goes for a strategic approach. He has good control in the center, while we still have to find a way to develop the light-squared bishop. }
6... Qxf6 7. Qa4+ { A typical check to force our knight to c6. } 7... Nc6
{ Forced. } 8. e3 { This was played the most often in practice. } 8... O-O
{ We bring the king to safety. } 9. cxd5
{ White keeps the center closed, but this opens up perspectives for our light-squared bishop. }
9... exd5 10. Be2 Be6
{ We continue our development. I prefer this to  10...a6  , although it's about the same thing. }
11. O-O a6 12. Rfc1
{ This line reached some popularity after Magnus Carlsen used it to win against Aronian in 2015. White has a long-term plan - Qd1, a3-b4, Na4-c5. }
12... Bd6
{ However, later on, it was discovered that Black gets a good position by going for an attack on the kingside. It turns out that White's position can become dangerous. }
13. Qd1
{ White's best bet - there are 2 plans available - a3 and b4, or Na4-c5. }
13... Ne7 { Regrouping the pieces. } 14. a3
{ Prepares b4. Basically, White has 2 main ideas here - a3 and b4, and Na4-c5. It's better to get the knight to c5 and then play b4 without a3, but we won't allow that and parry it with ...b6. }
14... Rfe8
{ With the idea to play ...Nf5 or ...g5. The rook will be useful on e8 if White plays e4 at some point. }
15. b4 Nf5
{ We're ready to push on the kingside. Probably it's good to go first ...h5 so as not to weaken the position too much. }
16. Na4 { Principled but slow. } 16... h5
{ It's better to push like this in order to keep options and not to weaken the position. }
17. Nc5
{ The knight reached the desired outpost, but White wasted a move on a3 - ideally he wanted to put the knight on c5 and go b4 in one go. }
17... Bc8 18. a4 g5
{ Black's attack looks serious. There is no e4 anymore, and the f5-knight is ideally placed. }
