[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5
{ One of the main moves to fight against the Ragozin. The pin is principled, and by not taking on d5 Black's c8-bishop remains shut off. The downside is that the c4-pawn is hanging. }
5... h6
{ By far the most played move. If the bishop retreats to h4 then it's good to take on c4. In over the board games, I also tried  5...dxc4  , transposing to a Vienna. However, I decided against recommending that because some lines are too forced, and if you forget some detail it can be decisive. }
6. Bxf6
{ White gives up the bishop and goes for a strategic approach. He has good control in the center, while we still have to find a way to develop the light-squared bishop. }
6... Qxf6 7. Qa4+ { A typical check to force our knight to c6. } 7... Nc6
{ Forced. } 8. e3 { This was played the most often in practice. } 8... O-O
{ We bring the king to safety. } 9. Be2 { Simple development. } 9... Bd7
{ The threat is ...Nxd4. White has to move the queen. } 10. Qb3
{ This is the more ambitious option - the idea is to take back on c4 with the queen. }
10... dxc4 11. Qxc4 { This is the point. } 11... Qe7
{ The queen was misplaced on f6, while here it defends the bishop and we can play ...Na5 and ...c5. }
12. a3 Bd6 { This time we keep the bishop and prepare ...e5. } 13. Ne4
{ Activates the knight. If  13.O-O  we can continue with  13...e5  . } 13... e5
{ The most principled reply. There was an interesting alternative  13...a5  14.O-O  a4  followed by ...Na5 and ...b5 with play on the queenside. Not a bad choice if you're trying to complicate matters. }
14. d5 { Otherwise, we just take on d4. } 14... Nb8
{ The best available spot for the knight. It will get back into play via a6 or d7. }
15. O-O f5 { Forces the events a bit. } 16. Nxd6 cxd6
{ Followed by ...Na6. The correspondence game Burmeister, F 2250 - Beetsma, M 2257 ICCF 2021 continued  17.Qc7  Na6  18.Bxa6  bxa6  19.Rac1  Rfc8  20.Qa5  Bb5  21.Rfe1  Qb7  22.h3  and a draw was agreed. }
