[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 5.Bg5 h6 − 7.e3 Main Line"]
[Black "7.e3 with 8.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5
{ One of the main moves to fight against the Ragozin. The pin is principled, and by not taking on d5 Black's c8-bishop remains shut off. The downside is that the c4-pawn is hanging. }
5... h6
{ By far the most played move. If the bishop retreats to h4 then it's good to take on c4. In over the board games, I also tried  5...dxc4  , transposing to a Vienna. However, I decided against recommending that because some lines are too forced, and if you forget some detail it can be decisive. }
6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. e3 { A solid move, simply continuing development. } 7... O-O 8.
a3
{ White loses a tempo to swap the bishop and hopes to start an attack with g4. }
8... Bxc3+ { Forced. } 9. bxc3 dxc4
{ Just to keep things simple. We're going to fianchetto the bishop to b7 and then break the center with ...c5. Thus White is not in time to try the attack with g4.Of course, the natural  9...c5  is also good, but it allows ideas with g4. For example,  10.g4  cxd4  11.cxd4  Nc6  12.h4  Qd8  13.g5  h5!  a typical reply  14.Nd2  g6  15.Bg2  Na5  16.cxd5  exd5  17.O-O  Be6  18.Rc1  Qd7  with good play for Black in Harsha, B 2582 - Hossain, E 2390 Delhi 2022. }
10. Bxc4 b6 { We prepare to fianchetto the bishop. } 11. e4
{ It's not dangerous. We'll be able to put pressure against the d4-pawn. }
11... Bb7 { Development first. } 12. Qe2 c5 { The typical break. } 13. O-O Nc6
{ It makes sense to attack the d4-pawn. Of course,  13...Nd7  is possible as well, if a bit more passive. }
14. Rad1 Rfd8
{ Next we can bring the other rook to c8. It's not easy for White to push the central pawns. Black has a nice position. }
*

