{ I thought for a long time about which line I want to recommend here. Most often Black goes  8...dxc4  followed by ...c5 which is good I played it too but it's too drawish. With ...Nc6 I tried to find the right balance between getting a playable position and avoiding forced lines.The line is quite popular nowadays, and Black has good results. It was also recommended in the Lifetime Repertoires: Nimzo Ragozin by Daniel Barrish and Christof Sielecki. }
9. Bd3 { Looks active but it allows the break ...e5. } 9... e5
{ We may take advantage of the move order and break the center immediately.  9...dxc4  10.Bxc4  would transpose. }
10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. cxd5 Rd8
{ That's a point to remember. It turns out that White cannot keep the d5-pawn. Note that we are not threatening immediately ...Rxd5 because of Bh7+. But there are various ideas like ...Bg4, ...Nxf3+, or ...c6. }
12. e4 { Secures the d5-pawn in advance. } 12... Bg4 13. Be2 Bxf3
{ Thus our knight won't budge from the center for some time. } 14. Bxf3 c6 15.
O-O Bxc3
{ We can go for some mass exchange and reach an equal position, or play on with  15...Qf4  . }
16. Rxc3 cxd5 17. exd5 Nxf3+ 18. Qxf3 Qxf3 { Forced. } 19. Rxf3 Rxd5
{ With a completely equal ending. } *

