[Round "?"]
[White "8) 5.Bg5 h6 − 7.e3 Main Line"]
[Black "7.e3 with 8.Rc1 & 9.Be2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5
{ One of the main moves to fight against the Ragozin. The pin is principled, and by not taking on d5 Black's c8-bishop remains shut off. The downside is that the c4-pawn is hanging. }
5... h6
{ By far the most played move. If the bishop retreats to h4 then it's good to take on c4. In over the board games, I also tried  5...dxc4  , transposing to a Vienna. However, I decided against recommending that because some lines are too forced, and if you forget some detail it can be decisive. }
6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. e3 { A solid move, simply continuing development. } 7... O-O 8.
Rc1
{ The most often played move. White makes a useful move and, in case of ...dxc4, wants to take back Bxc4 in one move. }
8... Nc6
{ I thought for a long time about which line I want to recommend here. Most often Black goes  8...dxc4  followed by ...c5 which is good I played it too but it's too drawish. With ...Nc6 I tried to find the right balance between getting a playable position and avoiding forced lines.The line is quite popular nowadays, and Black has good results. It was also recommended in the Lifetime Repertoires: Nimzo Ragozin by Daniel Barrish and Christof Sielecki. }
9. Be2
{ A subtle move, continuing development. Compared to  9.Bd3  there is no ...e5 anymore. }
9... dxc4
{ It makes sense to go for this since White will have to spend another tempo to take back. }
10. Bxc4 Bxc3+
{ Depending on how White takes back we will see where to develop the light-squared bishop. }
11. bxc3 b6
{ Now we can develop the bishop to b7. The push ...e5 is not so effective anymore because White has a strong center and can just ignore it. }
12. O-O Bb7 13. Bd3
{ The only way to fight for an advantage. Sometimes White can retreat the bishop to c2 or b1 and then Qd3. Another plan is to push e4. Whenever Black moves the knight to prepare ...c5, White goes Ne5 followed by f4. }
13... Nb8
{ I analysed this position a lot because it looks critical for the whole line. Finally, I decided upon this maneuver to bring the knight to d7 and push ...c5. It's true we're wasting some tempi like this, but we can challenge the white knight on e5, and from d7 our knight can also come to the king's defense - ...Nf8 or ...Nf6. }
14. Ne5
{ White takes this opportunity to activate his knight. If  14.e4  there is  14...c5  and it will transpose back into the main line of this variation. }
14... Qe7
{ Renews the idea of ...Nd7. The knight has to join the game as soon as possible. }
15. e4 Nd7 { The knight joins the game. } 16. Nc4
{ White tries to complicate the game by keeping the knights on the board. }
16... Nf6 17. Qe2 c5
{ We have to challenge White's center. After e5 White gets d6 for the knight, but we also get an outpost on d5. }
18. e5 Nd5 19. Qe4
{ If  19.g3  we can go  19...b5  20.Nd6  c4  21.Bc2  f5  with a good position. }
19... f5 { A strong resource. } 20. exf6 Nxf6
{ With an equal position - it's good to bring a rook to d8. } *

