{ By far the most played move. If the bishop retreats to h4 then it's good to take on c4. In over the board games, I also tried  5...dxc4  , transposing to a Vienna. However, I decided against recommending that because some lines are too forced, and if you forget some detail it can be decisive. }
6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. e3 { A solid move, simply continuing development. } 7... O-O 8.
Rc1
{ The most often played move. White makes a useful move and, in case of ...dxc4, wants to take back Bxc4 in one move. }
8... Nc6
{ I thought for a long time about which line I want to recommend here. Most often Black goes  8...dxc4  followed by ...c5 which is good I played it too but it's too drawish. With ...Nc6 I tried to find the right balance between getting a playable position and avoiding forced lines.The line is quite popular nowadays, and Black has good results. It was also recommended in the Lifetime Repertoires: Nimzo Ragozin by Daniel Barrish and Christof Sielecki. }
9. cxd5
{ White went for this in most of the games. Thus it avoids any breaks in the center. }
9... exd5 10. a3
{ White keeps things simple. Now we'll have to part with our bishop. } 10...
Bxc3+ { Forced, otherwise d5 falls. } 11. Rxc3 Ne7
{ A maneuver to remember. The knight is heading for f5 or g6, after first playing ...c6. For now, the c7-pawn is safe, since  12.Rxc7?  Nc6  traps the rook. }
12. Bd3 c6 { We secure the c-pawn. } 13. Ne5
{ White is looking for some activity. } 13... Bf5
{ The bishop trade is good for us. } 14. O-O Bxd3
{ In the internet game Kuzubov, Y 2642 - Sargsyan, S 2618 Tornelo 2021 Black had no problems. Here I think it was easier to trade the bishops straight away Black instead played  14...Rfe8    . }
15. Qxd3 Qe6
{ Nd7 was a threat. Our plan is to ...Nf5/Nc8 - d6. Once the knight reaches d6 Black's position could become preferable. A sample line goes  16.b4  a6  17.a4  Rfc8  18.Rfc1  Nf5  and the knight reaches d6. There is no time for  19.b5?  because of  19...axb5  20.axb5  c5! }
