[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 5.e3 − Introduction"]
[Black "5.e3 with 6.Bd2 & 7.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. e3
{ A classical approach, White reverts to the Nimzowitsch with e3.   It's a solid setup, but it will take some time to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
5... O-O
{ A flexible move. We'll decide on the next steps depending on what White does. }
6. Bd2 {  } 6... b6
{ By far the main move here, we're going to fianchetto the bishop.  Another interesting idea is  6...Nbd7!?  ,  in order to make it less attractive for White to take on d5 as we have not weakened our queenside. For example, after  7.cxd5  exd5  8.Qc2  we can instead play for ...c6 and ...Bd6. }
7. a3 { White tries to take our bishop. } 7... Bd6
{ We can keep the bishop for now. Here it's more active than on e7, although  7...Be7  was possible as well, of course. }
8. b4 { White grabs some space on the queenside. } 8... dxc4
{ We're opening the position. } 9. Bxc4 { 9.e4  could be met with  9...Be7  . }
9... Nbd7
{ It turns out the bishop is misplaced on d2, in this position it would have been better on b2. }
10. b5 { Just to stop ...c5. } 10... a6
{ In order to trade the rooks on the a-file. } 11. a4 axb5 12. axb5 Rxa1 13.
Qxa1 Bb7 14. Be2 e5
{ This break is just as effective.   Black enjoyed a nice position in the correspondence game Ergenekon, M 2422 - Ísólfsson, E 2464 ICCF 2017, which ended in a draw. }
*

