[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. e3
{ A classical approach, White reverts to the Nimzowitsch with e3.   It's a solid setup, but it will take some time to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
5... O-O
{ A flexible move. We'll decide on the next steps depending on what White does. }
6. Bd2 {  } 6... b6
{ By far the main move here, we're going to fianchetto the bishop.  Another interesting idea is  6...Nbd7!?  ,  in order to make it less attractive for White to take on d5 as we have not weakened our queenside. For example, after  7.cxd5  exd5  8.Qc2  we can instead play for ...c6 and ...Bd6. }
7. Bd3 { This is an inaccuracy. } 7... dxc4
{ White has to lose another tempo. } 8. Bxc4 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7
{ And we're ready to play ...c5. } 10. Qe2 c5 11. Rfd1 cxd4
{ It's good to exchange these pawns as soon as possible. } 12. Nxd4 a6 13. a3
Bd6
{ I already prefer Black's position, and I managed to win a nice game in 2022 against  IM John Cox 2319.  The rest of the game went:  14.Be1  Qe7  15.Rac1  b5  16.Ba2  Rac8  17.f3  Rfd8  18.e4  Bf4  19.Bd2  Bb8  20.Be1  Ne5  21.Bf2  Ng6  22.Nb3  Nf4  23.Qf1  Nd7  24.Ne2  Ng6  25.Rxc8  Rxc8  26.Rc1  Rd8  27.Na5  Ba8  28.Nc6  Bxc6  29.Rxc6  Nde5  30.Rxa6  Nd3  31.Be3  Qb7  32.Rb6  Qc7  33.Rxb8  Qxb8  34.Nd4  Nge5  35.f4  Ng4  36.Qxd3  Qb6  37.Qxb5  Qxb5  38.Nxb5  Rd1#  . }
