{ With the same idea as after  9.Rc1  to prevent  9...Bd6  because of  10.Nb5  .  This move became quite trendy recently, and indeed Black has to know what he's doing. }
9... c5
{ I prefer to go for counterplay immediately.  An example of how things can easily go wrong for Black is  9...Re8  10.a3  Bf8?!  11.Ng5!  g6  12.h4  c5?!  13.h5  and White got a crushing attack in Aronian, L 2785 - Esipenko, A 2723 Berlin 2022. }
10. O-O { White completes development. } 10... c4
{ Grabbing some space on the queenside. } 11. Be2
{ 11.Bf5  is not inspiring because the bishop can be easily driven away with  11...g6  . }
11... Nc6 12. b3 { Undermining the pawn chain. } 12... Rc8
{ After analyzing this position I came to the conclusion we need this rook here to support the c-pawn. The position gets very unbalanced.  A more quiet continuation is  12...Bxc3  13.Bxc3  b5  and although we are a tempo down compared to 10.a3, we've got a solid position. }
13. bxc4 dxc4
{ And a pawn structure imbalance is created. Each side will try to make the best of their passed pawns.   For the moment the White center looks nice but cannot advance. }
14. Qb2 { d5 is a threat. } 14... Bxc3
{ The knight was controlling the important squares e4 and d5. } 15. Bxc3 Ne7
{ This move opens up the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and now the c4-pawn is defended. }
16. a4 { A useful move, gaining some space on the queenside. } 16... Ng6
{ The position is unbalanced, but I think Black is doing fine. We have firm control over the e4- and d5-squares, and we can continue with ...Re8 and ...Qd5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 5.e3 − Introduction"]
[Black "6.Bd2 with 7.cxd5 & 8.Bd3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. e3
{ A classical approach, White reverts to the Nimzowitsch with e3.   It's a solid setup, but it will take some time to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
5... O-O
{ A flexible move. We'll decide on the next steps depending on what White does. }
6. Bd2 { An old plan that gained a lot of popularity recently. } 6... b6
{ By far the main move here, we're going to fianchetto the bishop.  Another interesting idea is  6...Nbd7!?  ,  in order to make it less attractive for White to take on d5 as we have not weakened our queenside. For example, after  7.cxd5  exd5  8.Qc2  we can instead play for ...c6 and ...Bd6. }
7. cxd5
{ Once we played ...b6, White goes for this.   The point is quite simple- we won't develop the bishop on the c8-h3 diagonal because of the weak white squares on the queenside. }
7... exd5 8. Bd3 { White wants to develop as quickly as possible. } 8... Bb7
{ Once we have played ...b6 the bishop belongs here. } 9. Qc2
{ With the same idea as after  9.Rc1  to prevent  9...Bd6  because of  10.Nb5  .  This move became quite trendy recently, and indeed Black has to know what he's doing. }
9... c5
{ I prefer to go for counterplay immediately.  An example of how things can easily go wrong for Black is  9...Re8  10.a3  Bf8?!  11.Ng5!  g6  12.h4  c5?!  13.h5  and White got a crushing attack in Aronian, L 2785 - Esipenko, A 2723 Berlin 2022. }
10. O-O { White completes development. } 10... c4
{ Grabbing some space on the queenside. } 11. Be2
{ 11.Bf5  is not inspiring because the bishop can be easily driven away with  11...g6  . }
11... Nc6 12. b3 { Undermining the pawn chain. } 12... Rc8
{ After analyzing this position I came to the conclusion we need this rook here to support the c-pawn. The position gets very unbalanced.  A more quiet continuation is  12...Bxc3  13.Bxc3  b5  and although we are a tempo down compared to 10.a3, we've got a solid position. }
13. bxc4 dxc4
{ And a pawn structure imbalance is created. Each side will try to make the best of their passed pawns.   For the moment the White center looks nice but cannot advance. }
14. Bxc4
{ This loses as we can instantly take advantage of the White pieces that have been so nicely lined up on the c-file for us. }
14... Na5 { The only winning move. The pin on the c-file will prove decisive. }
15. Bd3
{ Targets h7, and more importantly is the only move that stops us from playing ...Bxc3 followed by ...Ne4, winning a piece. }
15... Bxf3
{ Be careful! Both  15...Nd5?  and  15...Bxc3  16.Bxc3  Nd5?  are hasty and blunder a draw after Bxh7+ followed by Qf5.   However,  15...Bxc3  16.Bxc3  Bxf3  17.gxf3  is just a transposition. }
16. gxf3 Bxc3 17. Bxc3 Nd5
{ We can finally cash in on the pin but we must still be accurate. } 18. Bxh7+
Kh8 19. Qf5 { White's desperate last attempt to save the game. } 19... Rxc3
{ We can grab the piece safely but only with the rook!  19...Nxc3??  20.Qh5  would be unfortunate for us as the dual threats of Bg6/Bf5 will prove fatal. We need the knight on d5 to meet Qh5 with the ...Nf6 fork.  Otherwise  20.Qh3  is easily parried with  20...Qg5+  21.Kh1  Qh6  . }
