[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 5.e3 − Introduction"]
[Black "6.Bd2 with 7.cxd5 & 8.Bd3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. e3
{ A classical approach, White reverts to the Nimzowitsch with e3.   It's a solid setup, but it will take some time to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
5... O-O
{ A flexible move. We'll decide on the next steps depending on what White does. }
6. Bd2 {  } 6... b6
{ By far the main move here, we're going to fianchetto the bishop.  Another interesting idea is  6...Nbd7!?  ,  in order to make it less attractive for White to take on d5 as we have not weakened our queenside. For example, after  7.cxd5  exd5  8.Qc2  we can instead play for ...c6 and ...Bd6. }
7. cxd5
{ Once we played ...b6, White goes for this.   The point is quite simple- we won't develop the bishop on the c8-h3 diagonal because of the weak white squares on the queenside. }
7... exd5 8. Bd3 { White wants to develop as quickly as possible. } 8... Bb7
{ Once we have played ...b6 the bishop belongs here. } 9. O-O
{ 9.Ne5  is a bit early and after  9...Bd6  we're going to follow up with ...c5 and ...Nc6. And White has nothing better than to play  10.O-O  transposing to  9.O-O  . }
9... Bd6
{ The bishop is more active here than on e7. Without the rook on c1 White doesn't have Nb5, attacking both the bishop and the c7-pawn - we simply retreat the bishop to e7. }
10. Rc1 c5 11. Nb5
{ Basically White wants to gain a tempo with this- we're going to play ...Be7 and ...a6 in order to get the knight away. }
11... Be7
{ We keep the bishop, and the knight on b5 will have to go back sooner or later. }
12. Ne5 a6 13. Nc3 Nc6 { ...cxd4 can be a threat once White goes for f4. } 14.
Ne2 c4
{ After this the position becomes double-edged. We have to play by advancing the pawns on the queenside, while White will push on the other flank. An alternative is  14...Rc8  with a normal position, where we still keep the option to take on d4. }
15. Bb1 b5 { We need to push the pawns. } 16. f4 a5 17. Ng3 Ra6
{ The rook can be useful on the 6th rank. Also, there is an option to play ...Bc8 and control the f5-square. The position is complicated and playable for both sides. }
