{ Since  9...Bd6  can be met with  10.Nb5  and I don't want to spend a tempo on   9...a6  , this is the best square for the bishop.   9...Re8  followed by  10.--  Bf8  is quite a topical line nowadays, yet I prefer the text because it's not so forced. }
10. O-O c5 { We're going to play ...Nc6 next in order to put pressure on d4. }
11. dxc5 { Change of plans. } 11... bxc5 12. Re1
{ White is preparing e4 at the right moment, trying to claim a small edge in the resulting positions. }
12... Re8
{ A useful move. We still don't show where we're going to develop the b8-knight - it's either on d7 or on a6. A fine point is that with the d-file open, e4 is not dangerous in view of ...dxe4 and the bishop is hanging. }
13. e4 { This is not dangerous here. } 13... dxe4 14. Bxe4 { Forced. } 14...
Nxe4 { Our light-squared bishop is strong. } 15. Nxe4 Na6
{ The bishop pair fully compensates for the slightly worse structure. } *

