{ Since  9...Bd6  can be met with  10.Nb5  and I don't want to spend a tempo on   9...a6  , this is the best square for the bishop.   9...Re8  followed by  10.--  Bf8  is quite a topical line nowadays, yet I prefer the text because it's not so forced. }
10. O-O c5 { We're going to play ...Nc6 next in order to put pressure on d4. }
11. Ne5 { A typical move. } 11... Nc6 12. Ne2
{ 12.Ba6  Is a typical motif in positions where Black has Nc6, b6, and Bb7 and White has Ne5 and Bd3. We have to be careful about it, but here it doesn't give White anything. After  12...Qc7  we just have to defend the bishop. Following  13.Bxb7  Qxb7=  ,  the bishop trade was rather good for us. Now White is left with the dark-squared bishop which is less active. The position is about equal. }
12... Rc8 13. Bc3 Ne4
{ Leads to simplifications. An option to keep the game more complicated is  13...c4  followed by expansion on the queenside with ...b5 and so on. }
14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Bxe4 dxe4
{ Led to an equal position in the internet game ½-½ Vidit, S 2726 - So, W 2770 chess24.com 2021. }
