[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 5.e3 − Introduction"]
[Black "6.a3 with 7.bxc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. e3
{ A classical approach, White reverts to the Nimzowitsch with e3.   It's a solid setup, but it will take some time to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
5... O-O
{ A flexible move. We'll decide on the next steps depending on what White does. }
6. a3 { This seems a bit early. } 6... Bxc3+
{ We trade the bishop for a better structure. } 7. bxc3 c5
{ The most natural move. We're already fighting for the center. If White goes  8.Be2  or  8.Bd3  we just take on c4 transposing in the main line. }
8. cxd5 exd5
{ With the knight on f3 this position is not great for White. It's not easy to prepare e4 because f3 is not possible. In the meantime the dark square bishop is blocked and doesn't have any prospects. Here we're already threatening ...c4 to gain space. }
9. Be2 { Too passive. } 9... c4
{ Black's position is preferable. We can develop the pieces on active squares - ...Nc6, ...Re8, ...Bf5 while White cannot properly prepare e4. }
*

