1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. e3
{ A classical approach, White reverts to the Nimzowitsch with e3.   It's a solid setup, but it will take some time to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
5... O-O
{ A flexible move. We'll decide on the next steps depending on what White does. }
6. Bd3 dxc4
{ It's important to exchange the pawns now. If we go  6...c5  White can take on d5 and on c5 and create an isolated pawn. }
7. Bxc4 c5 8. a3 { This move gained in popularity recently. } 8... Bxc3+ 9.
bxc3 Qc7 { The c4-bishop is hanging. White has to do something about it. } 10.
Be2
{ White wants to improve his position and make use of the bishop pair in the long term. }
10... Nc6
{ I prefer to react actively to this setup, by preparing a quick ...e5.  10...b6  is played most often here, with ideas of either ...Bb7 or ...Ba6 to trade the bishops. Black shouldn't have problems there as well. }
11. Bb2 Rd8 { Prepares ...e5. } 12. Qc2 { Aimed against ...e5. } 12... Na5
{ We're using the pin on the c-file. } 13. O-O
{ 13.c4  allows  13...cxd4  and if  14.exd4  b5!  is strong  15.c5  Bb7  , with a good position for Black.  16.Bxb5?  is wrong due to  16...Rab8! }
13... cxd4 { Hoping to force White to spoil the pawn structure. } 14. c4
{ Playing for compensation. } 14... b6
{ Of course, we finish our development instead of opening up the position for the white bishops. }
15. Bxd4 Bb7
{ Followed by ...Rac8. White has the bishop pair but a slightly worse structure. }
