[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. e3
{ A classical approach, White reverts to the Nimzowitsch with e3.   It's a solid setup, but it will take some time to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
5... O-O
{ A flexible move. We'll decide on the next steps depending on what White does. }
6. Bd3 dxc4
{ It's important to exchange the pawns now. If we go  6...c5  White can take on d5 and on c5 and create an isolated pawn. }
7. Bxc4 c5 8. a3 { This move gained in popularity recently. } 8... Bxc3+ 9.
bxc3 Qc7 { The c4-bishop is hanging. White has to do something about it. } 10.
Qc2
{ White indirectly defends the c4-bishop and prepares either Bd3 or e4. However, the queen is a bit misplaced on c2 and will likely have to move away to e2 later on.   The immediate  10.Qe2?  was not possible due to  10...cxd4  11.cxd4  b5!  when White loses. }
10... b6
{ It makes sense to go for this with the white queen misplaced on c2. I think Black gets an easy play. It was also possible to continue similarly to the 10. Be2 lines, for example,  10...Nc6!?  11.Bd3  e5  12.O-O  Re8  13.dxe5  Nxe5  14.Nxe5  Qxe5  15.f3  Be6  16.c4  Rad8  with an equal position. }
11. Bd3
{ White's idea was to bring the bishop to this active position. Now the white queen is defended in case of a pawn trade on d4. }
11... Bb7 { We continue with our development. } 12. O-O Nbd7
{ The next step is to activate the rooks - ...Rac8 and ...Rfe8. } 13. Qe2
{ White is preparing e4. It was not possible to play immediately  13.e4?  due to  13...c4!  and the e4-pawn drops. }
13... Be4 { The bishop trade is good for us, and we're also stopping e4. } 14.
Bb2 { White needs to develop this bishop somehow. } 14... Bxd3
{ The bishop trade is good for Black. } 15. Qxd3
{ Until here we followed the game Blees, A 2391 - Alekseev, E 2626 Amsterdam 2016. }
15... Rac8
{ The rook belongs to the c-file. I like Black's position here. The white bishop doesn't have perspectives. Possible ideas are ...Rfe8 or ...cxd4 followed by ...Qc2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 5.e3 − Introduction"]
[Black "6.Bd3 with 7.Bxc4 & 8.a3 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. e3
{ A classical approach, White reverts to the Nimzowitsch with e3.   It's a solid setup, but it will take some time to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
5... O-O
{ A flexible move. We'll decide on the next steps depending on what White does. }
6. Bd3 dxc4
{ It's important to exchange the pawns now. If we go  6...c5  White can take on d5 and on c5 and create an isolated pawn. }
7. Bxc4 c5 8. a3 { This move gained in popularity recently. } 8... Bxc3+ 9.
bxc3 Qc7 { The c4-bishop is hanging. White has to do something about it. } 10.
Qd3
{ This is an interesting try, although it is rarely played. White aims for a quick e4-push. }
10... b6
{ I like the plan to fianchetto the bishop. Obviously if White doesn't do anything quickly we're getting a good position since the queen on d3 and the bishop on c4 are misplaced. }
11. O-O { This is possible, but White will not be in time to push e4 anymore. }
11... Bb7 { We're controlling the e4-square. } 12. Ne5
{ White tries to get Bb2 and f3 in order to push e4 later on. } 12... Rc8
{ We're targeting the c4-bishop. } 13. Bb2
{ White is not in time to coordinate his pieces. If  13.f3  we can go  13...cxd4  14.cxd4  Nfd7!?  so that the knight doesn't hang on f6 after we take on e5.  15.Nxd7  Qxc4  with an equal game. }
13... Nc6
{ The most accurate. We're attacking the e5-knight, and if it moves then the c4-bishop will not be defended. }
14. Nxc6 { The only way to stay in the game. } 14... cxd4
{ An interesting try, although taking back on c6 was also good. } 15. Ne7+
{ White gives up the knight in a more favourable way. } 15... Qxe7 16. cxd4
{ Until here we followed the correspondence game Evans, D 2355 - Pirhala, L 2343 ICCF 2012. }
16... Be4
{ This looks tempting, and if  17.Qe2  there is  17...b5  in order to open the c-file. Black has a good game due to the active pieces. White hopes to activate the dark-squared bishop in the long run, but for now, that's not possible. It's good for us if we manage to trade the light-squared bishops and get rid of White's bishop pair. }
