[Black "8.O-O with 9.exd4 & 10.Qe2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. e3
{ A classical approach, White reverts to the Nimzowitsch with e3.   It's a solid setup, but it will take some time to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
5... O-O
{ A flexible move. We'll decide on the next steps depending on what White does. }
6. Bd3 dxc4
{ It's important to exchange the pawns now. If we go  6...c5  White can take on d5 and on c5 and create an isolated pawn  7.cxd5  exd5  8.dxc5  . }
7. Bxc4 c5 8. O-O { The main move. } 8... cxd4
{ I decided to recommend the main line, first taking on d4 followed by ...b6. There are many variations here, but I think Black just needs to know the ideas and is doing fine. }
9. exd4 { White goes for this almost automatically. } 9... b6 10. Qe2
{ The plan is to go Rd1 and then either force Black to take on c3, or push d5. }
10... Bb7 11. Rd1 h6
{ Lately this move has become popular. The point is we don't allow White to go d5 as in the  11...Nbd7  line, and we also prevent Bg5 -  11...Nbd7  12.d5  Bxc3  13.dxe6  Bxf3  14.gxf3  fxe6  15.bxc3  Qc7  16.Bxe6+  Kh8  is a forced line leading to equality. }
12. Ne5
{ The knight is strong here and we have to be careful. White's plan is to switch the rook on the 3rd rank via Rd3-g3. }
12... Nc6
{ An important move to remember - we have the ...Ne7-f5 idea to defend against a white attack. Note that  12...Nbd7  is wrong in view of  13.Rd3!  with a strong attack. }
13. Bf4
{ Just going for development.  13.Bxe6  with the idea of  13...fxe6  14.Nxc6  Bxc6  15.Qxe6+  winning a pawn is strongly met by    13...Qd6!  The point is that  14.Nxc6  Qxc6  15.d5  Qe8  quickly wins the d5-pawn back, while any bishop retreat can be met with 14... Nxd4. We do not need to fear the pin down the d-file as we can play Rd8/Bc5 and also exploit the loose knight on e5.   And after  13.Rd3  there is  13...Ne7! }
13... Bxc3 { Looks like the simplest solution. } 14. Nxc6
{ A good in-between trade. If  14.bxc3  there is  14...Nd5  and there is no time for  15.Nxc6  because of  15...Nxf4  . }
14... Bxc6 15. bxc3 Rc8 { With good play against the hanging pawns. } *

