[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. e3
{ A classical approach, White reverts to the Nimzowitsch with e3.   It's a solid setup, but it will take some time to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
5... O-O
{ A flexible move. We'll decide on the next steps depending on what White does. }
6. Bd3 dxc4
{ It's important to exchange the pawns now. If we go  6...c5  White can take on d5 and on c5 and create an isolated pawn  7.cxd5  exd5  8.dxc5  . }
7. Bxc4 c5 8. O-O { The main move. } 8... cxd4
{ I decided to recommend the main line, first taking on d4 followed by ...b6. There are many variations here, but I think Black just needs to know the ideas and is doing fine. }
9. exd4 { White goes for this almost automatically. } 9... b6 10. Ne5 Bb7 11.
Qb3
{ A very concrete move.  11.Qe2?!  is not so good due to  11...Nc6!  , and   11.Bg5  simply transposes to 10. Bg5. }
11... Bxc3
{ My recommendation is to meet Qb3 with ...Bxc3 in these kind of positions. The point is there is no time to retreat the bishop. }
12. bxc3 Nc6
{ The right place for the knight. Worse is  12...Nbd7?!  due to  13.Rd1  with pressure. }
13. Bxe6
{ Very straightforward, White goes for tactics. For example  13...fxe6?  14.Nxc6  Bxc6  15.Qxe6+  with a double attack to win back the piece. }
13... Qc7
{ Of course we don't take the bishop. I should mention that  13...Qe8  leads to the same thing. }
14. Nxc6 Qxc6 15. Bh3 Bc8
{ A nice move though not the only good one. By exchanging the bishop we get good compensation and control over the light squares - c4 and d5. }
16. Bxc8 Raxc8 17. Bb2
{ The bishop looks misplaced here it's like a pawn!, but  17.Bd2  is met with  17...Ne4  . }
17... Nd5 18. g3 { Prevents ...Nf4. } 18... Rfe8
{ Black has very good compensation for the pawn and a nice position. There is no rush to take back the pawn on c3 since we can gradually improve the position, and the d5-knight looks great. }
