[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) 5.e3 − Main Line"]
[Black "10.Bg5 with 11.Re1 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. e3
{ A classical approach, White reverts to the Nimzowitsch with e3.   It's a solid setup, but it will take some time to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
5... O-O
{ A flexible move. We'll decide on the next steps depending on what White does. }
6. Bd3 dxc4
{ It's important to exchange the pawns now. If we go  6...c5  White can take on d5 and on c5 and create an isolated pawn  7.cxd5  exd5  8.dxc5  . }
7. Bxc4 c5 8. O-O { The main move. } 8... cxd4
{ I decided to recommend the main line, first taking on d4 followed by ...b6. There are many variations here, but I think Black just needs to know the ideas and is doing fine. }
9. exd4 { White goes for this almost automatically. } 9... b6 10. Bg5
{ The most often played move. } 10... Bb7 11. Re1 Nbd7 12. Rc1 h6
{ I like to include this move here. } 13. Bh4 { White maintains the pin. }
13... Rc8 14. Bd3 Be7 { The idea is to play ...Nh5 and trade the bishops. } 15.
Bb1 Re8
{ An adequate way to defend against the white battery with Bb1 and Qd3. } 16.
Qd3 Nf8
{ We safely defended h7 and we are ready to move the f6 knight to either h5 or d5. }
17. Ne5 { White takes this central outpost. } 17... Nd5
{ I like the knight in the center.  17...Nh5  was also tried in practice in order to trade the bishop. }
18. Bg3 Bb4 { Just to create some threats. } 19. Red1 Nxc3
{ Now it's a good moment to trade the knight because the c1 rook cannot go to d1. }
20. bxc3 Ba3 21. Rc2 Qd5 22. f3 Red8
{ With a good position for Black. I feel that White's pieces are misplaced. ...Qa5 can be an idea depending on what White does. }
*

