[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) 5.e3 − Main Line"]
[Black "10.Bg5 with 11.Ne5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. e3
{ A classical approach, White reverts to the Nimzowitsch with e3.   It's a solid setup, but it will take some time to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
5... O-O
{ A flexible move. We'll decide on the next steps depending on what White does. }
6. Bd3 dxc4
{ It's important to exchange the pawns now. If we go  6...c5  White can take on d5 and on c5 and create an isolated pawn  7.cxd5  exd5  8.dxc5  . }
7. Bxc4 c5 8. O-O { The main move. } 8... cxd4
{ I decided to recommend the main line, first taking on d4 followed by ...b6. There are many variations here, but I think Black just needs to know the ideas and is doing fine. }
9. exd4 { White goes for this almost automatically. } 9... b6 10. Bg5
{ The most often played move. } 10... Bb7 11. Ne5 Nbd7
{ We need to complete development. Here White has an opportunity to get a forced draw. I looked for alternatives, but they looked better for White if he knew what he was doing:  11...h6  12.Bh4  Nc6  13.Bxf6  Qxf6  14.Nd7  Qh4  15.Nxf8  Rxf8  was played in 0-1 Arvola, B 2471 - Carlsen, M 2855 Norway 2021 and here White can get a slightly better endgame after  16.a3  Be7  17.Bd3  Nxd4  18.Be4  Bxe4  19.Qxd4  Bc6  20.Qxh4  Bxh4  . }
12. Nxf7 { Is a one game try to unbalance the game. } 12... Rxf7
{ This looks like the safer choice. We don't want to get into theoretical debates whether ...Kxf7 can keep some material advantage or not. }
13. Bxe6 Qf8 14. Qb3 Bxc3 { It's good to simplify the position. } 15. bxc3 Re8
{ Brings the last piece into play. } 16. Bxf7+
{ White has to go for this. ...Rxe6 was threatened. } 16... Qxf7 17. Qxf7+ Kxf7
18. c4
{ All this happened in ½-½ Van Foreest, J 2701 - Wojtaszek, R 2687 Prague 2021. }
18... Ne4
{ Seems more straightforward.  18...Rc8  which was played in the game is also OK. }
19. Be3 Nd6
{ Putting some pressure on the c4-pawn. For example  20.Rfc1  Ba6  21.c5  Nc4  with an equal endgame. The knights have good squares and it's important that we've got a rook on the board. }
*

