1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. e3
{ A classical approach, White reverts to the Nimzowitsch with e3.   It's a solid setup, but it will take some time to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
5... O-O
{ A flexible move. We'll decide on the next steps depending on what White does. }
6. Bd3 dxc4
{ It's important to exchange the pawns now. If we go  6...c5  White can take on d5 and on c5 and create an isolated pawn  7.cxd5  exd5  8.dxc5  . }
7. Bxc4 c5 8. O-O { The main move. } 8... cxd4
{ I decided to recommend the main line, first taking on d4 followed by ...b6. There are many variations here, but I think Black just needs to know the ideas and is doing fine. }
9. exd4 { White goes for this almost automatically. } 9... b6 10. Bg5
{ The most often played move. } 10... Bb7 11. Qe2 Nbd7
{ A natural developing move. It was also possible to take on c3 immediately  11...Bxc3  . }
12. Ne5 Bxc3 { It seems easier to trade on c3 than to play  12...Rc8  . } 13.
bxc3 Rc8 14. Bb3 { A pawn sacrifice for activity. } 14... Rxc3
{ We have to accept the sacrifice. Note that all our pieces are developed, so we're not risking much. }
15. Rac1 { Takes control over the c-file. } 15... Rxc1 16. Rxc1 Nxe5
{ Forces the issue a bit. Also possible was to play  16...Bd5  . } 17. dxe5 h6
{ An important inclusion, otherwise Black is just losing. } 18. Rd1
{ If  18.Bh4  there is  18...Qd4  . } 18... Qc7 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. exf6 Qf4
{ Another important move - the queen is covering our king, and also we want to take the f6-pawn. }
21. Rd7 Ba8
{ With an equal position. Our king is safe. A draw was soon agreed in ½-½ Tomashevsky, E 2696 - Nakamura, H 2786 Moscow 2017. }
