[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 5.g3"]
[Black "5.g3 with 6.Qb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. g3
{ The fianchetto is always an option. White aims for a long time pressure in Catalan style. However, here ...Bb4 and Nc3 favour us. We're going to grab the c4-pawn and then hang onto it. }
5... O-O
{ A natural reply - the c4-pawn is not going anywhere. It's not favourable for White to trade the pawns on d5 as it opens up our light-squared bishop. However,  5...dxc4  is the same. }
6. Qb3
{ An attempt to keep the c4-pawn and consolidate the center, but it gives us good play.   6.cxd5  exd5  gives Black easy play because it opens up the light-squared bishop.   While  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.bxc3  dxc4  8.Bg2  transposes to the main line.   6.Bg2  The logical follow-up. }
6... c5 { We're fighting for the center. } 7. Bg2
{ White cannot postpone this for too long. } 7... Nc6
{ Threatens ...cxd4 or ...Na5. } 8. cxd5 exd5
{ Black has a comfortable position - the white king is still in the center, ...cxd4 is a threat, and also ...c4 is a good option.   A sample line goes  9.a3  when probably the best is  9...c4  , gaining some space with tempo  10.Qc2  Ba5  11.O-O  h6  with a good position for Black. }
*

