7... Nc6
{ A useful move - it puts some pressure on the white center, and prevents Ne5. }
8. Qa4
{ A multi-purpose move. It prepares Bg5 and Rd1, but there is also the direct threat of Ne5. }
8... Nd5
{ This is intended to take advantage of the queen's exposed position. } 9. Qc2
{ Threatens e4 with tempo. } 9... Be7
{ This looks like a dance of the pieces back and forth. We want to meet e4 with ...Ndb4. }
10. Rd1 { Prepares e4 anyway, but the d4-pawn had to be defended first. } 10...
Rb8 { We're going to support the c4-pawn! } 11. e4 Ndb4
{ This looks natural.  11...Ncb4  12.Qb1  Nxc3  13.bxc3  Nd3  is possible as well. We'd lose the c4-pawn after  14.Qb5  , but trade some pieces on the way. }
12. Qe2 { It's good to keep the queen more central. } 12... Nd3 13. Be3
{ Defends the d4-pawn. } 13... b5 { We support our extra pawn on c4. } 14. b3
Ba6 { The best place for the bishop. } 15. d5
{ White has to go for this sooner or later. } 15... exd5 16. Nxd5 Bd6
{ With an unclear position. Both sides have their assets. We've got an extra pawn and the d3-knight looks great, but White will probably be able to exchange it. A sample line goes  17.Ne1  Nxe1  18.Qxe1  Ne5  the second knight is going to d3!  19.Bxa7  Ra8  20.Bd4  Nd3  . }
