1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. g3
{ The fianchetto is always an option. White aims for a long time pressure in Catalan style. However, here ...Bb4 and Nc3 favour us. We're going to grab the c4-pawn and then hang onto it. }
5... O-O
{ A natural reply - the c4-pawn is not going anywhere. It's not favourable for White to trade the pawns on d5 as it opens up our light-squared bishop. However,  5...dxc4  is the same. }
6. Bg2 dxc4
{ We take the pawn. It's not easy for White to take back the pawn because of the c3-knight. }
7. O-O
{ The most natural move. In the Catalan, White usually develops the kingside and then tries his best to get the pawn back. }
7... Nc6
{ A useful move - it puts some pressure on the white center, and prevents Ne5. }
8. a3
{ The main move. Now in the case of the trade on c3, we don't have ...c5 anymore. }
8... Be7
{ It looks best to keep the bishop and also the c4-pawn!. }
9. e4 { White gets a nice center, but for now cannot get the pawn back. } 9...
a6
{ We want to reinforce the pawn chain with ...b5. I also looked at  9...Na5  , but I think the text is better. }
10. Bf4
{ This is White's most popular option. The bishop is more active than on e3, but it doesn't defend the d4-pawn. }
10... b5 { We continue our idea. } 11. Qe2
{ With the idea to bring the rook to d1 and prepare d5. This is better than Qc2 because now taking on d4 is not as good as before - White gets enough compensation. }
11... Bb7 { We continue development. } 12. Rad1 { Preparing d5. } 12... Na5
{ A typical reply to prevent d5. The knight is heading to b3. } 13. Ne5
{ It's tempting to centralize the knight, but it takes away the e5 push. }
13... Nb3 { Our knight had no business on a5. } 14. d5
{ White breaks up the center. } 14... exd5 15. exd5 Bd6
{ Black has an advantage, but precision is required because the position is very sharp. First, we must block the d5-pawn. }
16. Nc6 Qd7 { The best square available for the queen. } 17. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ Only like this. } 18. Ne7+ Kh8 19. Nf5
{ Until here, we followed Flom, G 2457 - Beliavsky, A 2526 Skopje 2019. }
19... Qb6
{ This is important and it gives Black an advantage. The point is the queen defends the f6-knight, and also doesn't allow White to go Qe3-g5. We can play ...Rae8 next. }
