{ The fianchetto is always an option. White aims for a long time pressure in Catalan style. However, here ...Bb4 and Nc3 favour us. We're going to grab the c4-pawn and then hang onto it. }
5... O-O
{ A natural reply - the c4-pawn is not going anywhere. It's not favourable for White to trade the pawns on d5 as it opens up our light-squared bishop. However,  5...dxc4  is the same. }
6. Bg2 dxc4
{ We take the pawn. It's not easy for White to take back the pawn because of the c3-knight. }
7. O-O
{ The most natural move. In the Catalan, White usually develops the kingside and then tries his best to get the pawn back. }
7... Nc6
{ A useful move - it puts some pressure on the white center, and prevents Ne5. }
8. a3
{ The main move. Now in the case of the trade on c3, we don't have ...c5 anymore. }
8... Be7
{ It looks best to keep the bishop and also the c4-pawn!. }
9. e4 { White gets a nice center, but for now cannot get the pawn back. } 9...
a6
{ We want to reinforce the pawn chain with ...b5. I also looked at  9...Na5  , but I think the text is better. }
10. Be3
{ It's good to defend the d4-pawn in advance. The drawback is that Black can get ...Ng4 with tempo at some point. }
10... b5
{ We continue our idea. Now White has to decide how to fight for the initiative. }
11. h4
{ This push gives White's attacking chances a boost - the idea is to play e5 followed by Ng5. However, it cedes control over the g4-square, where our knight can jump at the right moment. }
11... Rb8
{ The rook is better off here - we can even prepare ...b4. An interesting option is the immediate  11...Ng4  12.Bf4  and now  12...e5!?  a pawn sac in order to activate our pieces  13.dxe5  h6  with an unclear position. We can follow up with ...Bc5 or ...Be6. }
