1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qb3
{ This is one of the most solid replies for White in the Ragozin, and we will find out why soon. }
5... c5
{ The most common and logical move, we defend the bishop and fight for the center at the same time. }
6. cxd5 exd5 { The most logical way to recapture the pawn. } 7. Bg5 Nc6
{ Attacks d4 and with the idea to push ...c4. } 8. e3
{ This was played in several games, and White tries to keep more tension in the center.   8.dxc5  is the correct way to handle this position, and it transposes into lines we will examinehere. }
8... c4
{ Definitely a plan to remember. Not only it comes with tempo, but we gain a lot of space on the queenside. }
9. Qc2
{ Actually, in some games this position was reached with White to move - there White had played Qc2 instead of Qb3. Of course, Black has a pleasant position being a tempo up. }
9... h6
{ Black is already doing well, but a few precise moves can increase the advantage.   The point here is to get rid of the pin. }
10. Bh4 g5 { We continue with our plan. } 11. Bg3 Ne4
{ And this was the point, of course. } 12. Nd2
{ White has to get rid of our strong knight. } 12... Bf5
{ Developing, and reinforcing the knight.  A sample line can be  13.Ndxe4  Bxe4  14.Qd2  Qe7  15.f3  Bg6  with a preferable position for Black. We have a pleasant choice to castle on either side. }
*

