1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qb3
{ This is one of the most solid replies for White in the Ragozin, and we will find out why soon. }
5... c5
{ The most common and logical move, we defend the bishop and fight for the center at the same time. }
6. dxc5 { The most often played move, the threat on the bishop is renewed. }
6... Nc6
{ One of two good moves in this position, the other being  6...Na6  , but I prefer  6...Nc6  because the knight has a more natural position here. }
7. Bg5 { White is counting on this pin. } 7... Qa5
{ An active move putting pressure on the a5-e1 diagonal.  Note that  7...dxc4  followed by ...Qa5 is the same thing. }
8. Bxf6 dxc4
{ It's important to remember this zwischenzug, otherwise White can take on d5 and spoil our pawn structure. }
9. Qxc4 gxf6 10. Rc1
{ Secures the c3 knight. Afterward White completes development and then will try to play against our doubled pawns. }
10... Qxc5 { Of course, we take back the pawn. } 11. Qh4
{ By far the most popular move- the queen keeps an eye on both our weak pawns - h7 and f6. }
11... Ke7
{ Yes, the king is safe here. However, we'll have to be a bit careful about tactical tricks. If we trade the queens, the king will have a great position. }
12. g3 Bxc3+
{ It's a good moment to make this exchange. Now White has to make a decision. }
13. bxc3
{ The main attempt. White also gets doubled pawns, but he will try to prove our king is weak. }
13... b6 { A logical move. } 14. Bg2 Bb7 15. O-O Rac8
{ Prevents White from playing Nd4.   Our plan is to play ...h5 and then bring the other rook to d8. }
16. Rfd1 h5
{ The pawn was hanging on h7, and now we're ready to play ...Rhd8.   Basically, Black's position is very sound. With correct play, the king is not in danger at all. I will give a few lines to show how the game can continue. }
17. Ne1 { It makes sense to redeploy the knight to d3. } 17... Rhd8
{ The immediate  17...Qg5  is possible as well, but we can just continue with our plan. }
18. Nd3 Qg5 { It's tempting to harass the white queen. } 19. Qa4
{ Finally White has some threats against our king. } 19... Qa5
{ We have to parry Qa3+.   White will have to move the queen away and the position is about equal.   White could also force doubled a-pawns with  20.Bxc6  and 21. Qxa5, but the position remains equal. }
