1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qb3
{ This is one of the most solid replies for White in the Ragozin, and we will find out why soon. }
5... a5 { This is an interesting option to keep the game more complicated. } 6.
a3
{ White insists on getting rid of the pin, but I think it's a bit too early for that, and it gives us good play. }
6... a4
{ With this important in-between move, we free up the a5-square that our queen can use later on.  And, of course, the bishop is untouchable at the moment  7.Qxb4?  Nc6  8.Qb5  Ra5  . }
7. Qc2 { A good square for the queen. } 7... Bxc3+
{ It's better not to retreat the bishop, as we don't want to lose important tempi, so we can act quickly in the center. }
8. Qxc3
{ White keeps the pawn structure intact, and the c4-pawn defended.   8.bxc3  allows us to take the c4-pawn with  8...dxc4  and after  9.e4  we can hold on to it with  9...b5  . }
8... Ne4 { This comes with tempo, and also prevents the pin with Bg5. } 9. Qc2
c5
{ This is the right time for a center-break, and at the same time intending the queen sortie to a5 }
10. e3 { White is trying to finish development. } 10... Qa5+
{ This is the easiest, although  10...cxd4  works as well. } 11. Bd2 Nxd2
{ We're getting rid of the bishop pair. } 12. Qxd2 cxd4
{ This is a good time to clarify the situation in the center. } 13. Nxd4 dxc4
{ We trade the pawns so that we don't get an isolated pawn on d5. } 14. Qxa5
Rxa5 15. Bxc4 Bd7
{ The endgame is equal, but comfortable for Black.   We can continue with ...Ke7, ... Rc8, ...e5, ...Rc5, and so on. }
