1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qb3
{ This is one of the most solid replies for White in the Ragozin, and we will find out why soon. }
5... a5 { This is an interesting option to keep the game more complicated. } 6.
cxd5
{ This exchange makes sense, due to the fact that the inclusion of Qb3 and ...a5 favors White. }
6... exd5
{ The natural reply. Now our plan is to castle and then break the center with ...c5. }
7. Bg5 { The best move, otherwise ...c5 or ...Ne4 are possible. } 7... O-O
{ A useful move, preparing counterplay with ...c5. } 8. e3
{ White continues development.  It was wrong to snatch a pawn with  8.Bxf6  Qxf6  9.Qxd5?  because of  9...Rd8  followed by ...c5 with a strong initiative. }
8... c5
{ The right moment to break the center.   Note that if White does nothing about it, both ...c4 and ...a4 are a threat. }
9. dxc5 { Pretty much forced. } 9... Be6
{ Here is our idea- the bishop does a great job defending the d5 pawn, while also threatening ...d4.   We're going to recapture the pawn by means of ...Nbd7, followed by ...Rc8 and ...Nxc5. }
10. Qc2 { The queen moves away from danger. } 10... h6
{ This is an important finesse. By driving the bishop back we keep the resource ...g5 in reserve.  In case of  11.Bf4  the easiest is to just continue our plan with  11...Nbd7  . }
11. Bh4 Nbd7 { All according to plan. } 12. Bb5
{ White is trying to use the b5-square somehow.  If White goes  12.a3  we can see the usefulness of including h6. Then after  12...Bxc3+  13.Qxc3?  is wrong in view of  13...g5!  followed by ...Ne4. }
12... Nxc5
{ We take back the pawn immediately, although  12...Rc8  was also possible. }
13. O-O Rc8
{ Threatening ...Nce4, and despite the isolated pawn, Black got a comfortable position due to the active pieces.  The correspondence game Mesquita Jr. 2296 - Cleto Jr. 2278 ICCF 2017 continued  14.Ne2  Qb6  15.Nfd4  Nce4  16.Qd3  Ng4  with a promising position for Black. }
