1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qc2
{ A playable but not very ambitious move. White tries to get some sort of Qc2 Nimzo, with Nf3 and d5 included. By defending the c3-knight White is ready to go either a3 or Bg5 next. }
5... c5
{ A principled move and one that fits well with our repertoire. There were options like  5...dxc4  6.e4  b5  7.a4  c6  grabbing a pawn, or the natural   5...O-O  which can lead to a Qc2 Nimzo after  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  . }
6. a3 { White goes after the dark-squared bishop similar to the Qc2 Nimzo. }
6... Bxc3+ { There is no need to try and keep the bishop. } 7. bxc3
{ Reinforcing the center.  7.Qxc3  was not so good because of  7...cxd4  . }
7... O-O
{ A useful move. We are ready to act in the center depending on what White does next. }
8. Bg5
{ An attempt to justify the early Qc2.  Note that  8.e3  transposes to5. e3. }
8... dxc4
{ We're starting trading the central pawns. The other capture  8...cxd4  was also possible. }
9. e3 { White has to hurry with development. } 9... cxd4
{ Continuing the strategy to break the center, as White is lagging in development. }
10. Bxf6
{ It's a pity to give up the bishop just like that and release the pin. However,  10.cxd4?  was wrong due to  10...Qa5+!  The white king is stuck in the center.  11.Qd2  c3  looks unpleasant for White. }
10... Qxf6
{ The safer choice. We could try to complicate matters with  10...gxf6  11.cxd4  b5  and hang onto the c4-pawn, for example  12.a4  Qa5+  13.Nd2  Bb7  with an unclear position. }
11. cxd4 { Otherwise White gets a bad pawn structure. } 11... Nc6
{ We cannot keep the c4-pawn, but we're preparing to break the center with ...e5. }
12. Bxc4 { White needs to take the pawn back. } 12... e5
{ With an equal position. White has to exchange everything on e5, because  13.d5?  is well met with  13...e4! }
