{ A playable but not very ambitious move. White tries to get some sort of Qc2 Nimzo, with Nf3 and d5 included. By defending the c3-knight White is ready to go either a3 or Bg5 next. }
5... c5
{ A principled move and one that fits well with our repertoire. There were options like  5...dxc4  6.e4  b5  7.a4  c6  grabbing a pawn, or the natural   5...O-O  which can lead to a Qc2 Nimzo after  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  . }
6. cxd5 { White clears the center and prepares Bf4 or Bg5. } 6... exd5 7. Bf4
{ White just wants to develop his pieces. } 7... Ne4
{ It looks like a good idea to go for this since White didn't pin our knight. We're putting more pressure on the c3-knight and prepare ...Bf5. It was also possible to go  7...c4  to grab more space. }
8. e3
{ White needs to complete development. If  8.dxc5  there is  8...Bf5  9.e3  Nd7  ,  and we'll take the pawn back by ...Ndxc5. }
8... Qa5
{ It makes sense to put more pressure on the c3-knight, and also to take away the option of Bb5+ due to ...Qxb5.   8...Bf5  is also good. }
9. Rc1 { White defends the c3-knight. } 9... Bf5
{ With the threat of ...Ng3. White played the opening passively, which allowed us to start active play.   If  10.dxc5  we can go  10...Nd7  , and not  10...Ng3?  because of  11.Qb3  Nxh1  12.a3  Bxc3+  13.Rxc3  , when Black is in big trouble despite being a rook up. }
