1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qc2
{ A playable but not very ambitious move. White tries to get some sort of Qc2 Nimzo, with Nf3 and d5 included. By defending the c3-knight White is ready to go either a3 or Bg5 next. }
5... c5
{ A principled move and one that fits well with our repertoire. There were options like  5...dxc4  6.e4  b5  7.a4  c6  grabbing a pawn, or the natural   5...O-O  which can lead to a Qc2 Nimzo after  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  . }
6. cxd5 { White clears the center and prepares Bf4 or Bg5. } 6... exd5 7. Bg5
{ The principled move, pinning our knight. } 7... h6
{ As usual, we insert this useful move. We want to have options to push ...g5 in case the bishop retreats. }
8. Bh4
{ Maintaining the pin.  8.Bxf6  is not challenging, as  8...Qxf6  9.a3  Bf5  comes with tempo.  10.Qa4+  Bd7  and Black is doing well. }
8... c4
{ Here we are at a crossroads. I analyzed this position a lot and Black has several ways to continue. In the end, I settled upon the space-grabbing ...c4 which was not played so far but makes a lot of sense. The early Qc2 is not so useful for White.   8...O-O  is possible, as well as  8...g5  9.Bg3  Ne4  10.dxc5  Qa5  11.Nd2  and so on.   Interesting is  8...cxd4  9.Nxd4  Nc6  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.a3!?  Bd6  12.e3  O-O  13.Be2  Rb8  14.O-O  . Black is fine here, but it's not to everyone's taste to play with hanging pawns. }
9. e4
{ A computer suggestion, only enough for equality. It's not easy to come up with this over the board as e3 or Nd2 looks more natural. }
9... g5
{ This is why ...h6 was useful! We need to get out of the pin in order to take on e4. }
10. Bg3 { Forced. } 10... Nxe4
{ We grab the important pawn by activating the knight. Note that  10...dxe4?  would be wrong due to  11.Ne5  , when Black is in trouble. }
11. Bxc4
{ This is the point of White's play. White trades the e-pawn for the c-pawn, and opened up the position. We're not winning a piece, since  11...Nxg3  is met by  12.Bb5+  and White saves the bishop. }
11... Nc6
{ This is a good moment to develop the pieces. Now ...Nxg3 is a threat as there is no more Bb5+.  11...O-O  or  11...Bf5  was also good, with the same idea - to complete development. }
12. Bd3
{ Once White got rid of the c4-pawn, d3 is a good place for the bishop. } 12...
O-O { Let's not forget the king in the center! } 13. O-O
{ Now the e4-knight is under attack. } 13... Bxc3
{ We make this trade so that we can keep the knight on e4. } 14. bxc3 Bf5
{ We just finished development. The knight on e4 is great and is well supported. The bishop is covering our king. The position looks about equal. ...Rc8 will be our next move to create some threats - ...Nb4 or ...g4 and ...Nxd4. Also ...Re8 and ...b6 if White puts a rook on b1 can be useful moves. }
