[White "Model Games"]
[Black "1. Nanu, Costica-Ciprian vs Parligras, Mircea-Emilian (Romanian Championship, Eforie Nord, 2022)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 Nbd7 8.
e3 g5 9. Bg3 Ne4 10. Nd2 Nxg3
{ 10...Nxc3?!  it's not good to take the pawn.  11.bxc3  Bxc3  12.Rc1  Ba5  13.Bd3↑  White gets a strong initiative due to the lead in development and the weaknesses on the kingside. }
11. hxg3 Nb6 12. a3 Bf8
{ 12...Bd6  13.Qc2  c6  prevents Nb5.  14.e4⩲  with a pleasant position for White.   12...Be7  is the recommendation in the course, since White already played e3. The text will later transpose to the course anyway. }
13. Bd3 c6 14. Qc2
{ If he had played  14.Na4  directly, I would probably not have exchanged the knights, but played  14...Be6  instead. }
14... Be6 15. Na4 { The knight is heading towards c5. } 15... Nxa4
{ I was tempted to trade the knights since he wasted a tempo on Qc2. } 16. Qxa4
{ Now it won't be easy for me to castle long since a7 is hanging. } 16... h5
{ Here it was a critical moment in the game. I wasn't sure how to develop my pieces, so I decided to push on the kingside instead. }
17. b4
{ Ciprian starts playing on the queenside. His ideas are either b5, or Nb3-c5. During the game this looked dangerous, but in the analysis it turned out it wasn't the best.  17.O-O-O  was preferable. }
17... a5 { I wanted to force the events.  17...Bd6  was a good alternative. }
18. b5 c5
{ My idea was to break the center like this. Until here, the line is covered in the course. }
19. dxc5
{ 19.e4?!  at first Ciprian wanted to open up the center like this, but Black is better after  19...Bg7∓   19.b6+!  not an easy decision, but this was the best.  19...Bd7  20.Bb5  White manages to trade a bishop.  20...Bxb5  21.Qxb5+  Qd7  22.Qe2  g4  with a balanced position. }
19... Bxc5 20. Nb3 Bb6
{ An ideal spot for the bishop - it cannot be attacked and controls important squares like e3 and d4. }
21. Nd4 Qf6 22. Rc1 h4
{ Continuing my play on the kingside.   22...Kd7∓  was also a good option. The king is safe in the center just in this case and I can fight for the c-file later on. }
23. Nxe6
{ Leads to an opposite coloured bishops position which is pleasant for Black. }
23... fxe6 24. gxh4 Rxh4
{ Here I considered several options.   24...Rf8!?  I took into account this in-between move.  25.O-O   25.Qc2  gxh4  26.Rh3  Kd7-+  the white queen is passive.  25...Rh8!  Black gets a strong attack.   24...gxh4!  the natural move. Now I can attack the white queen if it goes to g4, but I didn't want to allow Rh3.  25.Rh3  Kd7  26.Rf3  Qg7  and still with a large advantage for Black. }
25. Rxh4 gxh4
{ My bishop is much more active than White's which makes all the difference! }
26. Qg4 { The queen is covering the kingside. } 26... Kd7 27. a4
{ A useful move. In some lines I was considering going after the a-pawn - not anymore. }
27... Rf8 28. Rc2 Kd6
{ A strong move - the black king is safe in the center and there is a threat of ...Bc5!. White has no useful move. }
29. g3
{ White loses after this, but there is no good alternative anyway.   29.Qh5  I was calculating during the game.  29...Rf7∓  White's position is difficult. }
29... Qa1+ { This check decides the game. } 30. Qd1
{ 30.Ke2  Qg1-+  the point - White cannot defend f2. } 30... Qxd1+
{ 30...Qg7-+  probably wins faster. White's position is hopeless due to the weak king. }
31. Kxd1 hxg3 32. fxg3 Bxe3
{ I considered the endgame completely winning due to the connected d and e-pawns. }
33. Rh2 Rf2 { Forcing the rook trade.   33...Rg8-+ } 34. Rxf2 Bxf2 35. g4 Bh4
36. b6 Bd8 37. Ke2 e5 38. Bf5 e4 39. Bc8 Kc6 40. Be6 Bxb6 41. g5 Bd4 42. g6 Kd6
43. Bc8 b5 { Here I calculated the forced win until the end.   43...b6-+ } 44.
axb5 a4 45. b6 a3 46. b7 Kc7
{ A good Ragozin game which helped me become the Romanian Champion in 2022! } *

