{ In the course I gave  9...Bd7  following my game against Petkov. The text is a good alternative. }
10. Qxd4
{ 10.cxd4  keeps the pawn structure intact.  10...Bd7!?  although it takes some time it's worth it to activate the bishop.   10...Nc6  this is also natural.  11.Qc2  Bc6  12.Qxc4  Bd5  with easy play for Black. }
10... Nc6 11. Qxc4 e5 12. Bg5 h6 13. Rfd1
{ Magnus tries for more.   13.Bxf6  was the way to go, but the position is just equal.  13...Qxf6  14.Nd2  Qe7= }
13... Be6
{ An important detail, which gives Black a good position.   13...Qe7?!  would play into White's hands.  14.Bxf6  Qxf6  15.Nd2⩲  with a small edge due to the extra tempo - the rook on d1, which is quite useful. }
14. Rxd8 Bxc4 15. Rxa8 Rxa8 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Kf1
{ Natural but slow.   17.Rd1!?  a simple solution was to sac a pawn in order to get activity.  17...Bxe2   17...Rc8  18.Bh3  Rc7  19.Kf1∞  White controls the open file.  18.Rd7=∞  White has compensation for the pawn due to the active pieces. }
17... Rd8 18. Ke1 Na5 19. Rd1 Rc8
{ A good decision, Black keeps the game going. } 20. Nd2 Be6 21. c4
{ 21.Ne4!  recommended by the engines. Not an obvious line though.  21...f5  22.Nd6  Rxc3  23.Bxb7⇆  the strong knight on d6 ensures White enough compensation. However, it was difficult to find such a line. }
21... Bxc4 22. Nxc4 Rxc4 23. Rd8+ Kg7 24. Bd5 Rc7 25. Ra8
