{ This attempt to break the pawn chain backfires.   28.Rd8  Kf6  29.h4⩱ } 28...
Rc5 29. Ba2 Nc4
{ 29...fxg4  30.Rxe4  f5-+  Black is a pawn up and should be winning. } 30. a4
{ 30.Bxc4!  it's easy to miss, but this was the way to make a draw. At the press conference, both players admitted they considered the resulting position winning for Black.  30...Rxc4  31.gxf5  Ra4  32.Rb8!  excellent, the rook gets active and doesn't allow the black king to come into play.  32...b5  33.Rb6  the black king is cut off from play.  33...Rxa3  34.Kd2⇆  Black cannot push his pawns because White activates his king. }
30... Nd6 31. Re7 fxg4
{ 31...Rc2!  this is the accurate way to win.  32.Bb3  Rc3-+ } 32. Rd7 e3 33.
fxe3 Ne4 34. Kf1 Rc1+
{ Very natural, but misses the win.   34...Rf5+!  35.Kg2  b5-+  Black should be able to convert the extra pawn. }
35. Kg2 Rc2 36. Bxf7 Rxe2+ 37. Kg1 Re1+ 38. Kg2 Re2+ 39. Kg1 Kf6 40. Bd5
{ 40.Rxb7!  would lead to a draw. However it's extremely difficult to find the line over the board, and let's not forget it was move 40!  40...Ng5  41.Bh5!  Nf3+  42.Kf1  Rc2  43.h4= }
40... Rd2 41. Rf7+ Kg6 42. Rd7
{ 42.Re7!  Rxd5  43.Rxe4  Kf5  44.Rb4  Rd7  would give White good chances for a draw. }
42... Ng5 { Now it's all over. } 43. Bf7+ Kf5
{ 43...Kf6!  was slightly more precise. } 44. Rxd2 Nf3+ 45. Kg2 Nxd2 46. a5 Ke5
{ Black is winning. } 47. Kg3 Nf1+ 48. Kf2 Nxh2 49. e4 Kxe4 50. Be6 Kf4 51. Bc8
Nf3 52. Bxb7 Ne5 53. Bxa6 Nc6 54. Bb7 Nxa5 55. Bd5 h5 56. Bf7 h4 57. Bd5
{ A nice and instructive endgame! After this game Magnus Carlsen withdrew from the tournament, the first time he ever did that! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "4. Villamayor, Buenaventura vs Maghsoodloo, Parham (Sheikh Kamal Online Invitational, Tornelo, 2021)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. Ne5 Bd7 7. Nxd7 Nxd7 8.
e3 Nb6 9. Qb3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nxc4 11. Qxc4 Qd5 12. Qxd5 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 exd5
{ Please check the course for detailed analysis until here! } 14. Rb1
{ Trying to activate the rook, but it rather wastes time. } 14... O-O-O 15. Ke2
Na5 { This is the usual plan - the knight has a nice outpost on c4. } 16. Kd3
f5 { White's only counterplay is by pushing e4, and the text just stops that. }
17. h3 { 17.f3  Rhe8⩱ } 17... h5
{ Stops g4 but loses valuable time.   17...Nc4∓  was actually more accurate.  18.g4  Rhf8  the game opens in Black's favour. }
18. Ba3
{ With the idea to activate the bishop via e7-g5. However this takes too long and doesn't solve White's problems.   18.f3!  with the idea e4 was necessary. White is in the game. }
18... Nc4 19. Be7 Rde8 20. Bg5 h4 21. Bf4
{ 21.g3!  was essential, but it's not easy to completely give up control over e4 just like that.  21...hxg3  22.fxg3  Re6⩱ }
21... Rh5 22. Rhe1 g5 23. Bh2 Rh6
{ White is too passive here and can only sit and watch as Black improves his position. }
24. Rb5 c6 25. Rbb1 Rhe6 26. Re2 f4 27. Rbe1 fxe3 28. fxe3 Re4 29. Bg1 g4 30.
hxg4 Rxg4 31. Bf2 Rxg2 32. Bxh4 Rxe3+
{ A nice finish. In this game we saw that an apparently equal endgame was in fact much easier to play for Black.   32...Rxe3+  33.Rxe3  Rd2 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "5. Palac, Mladen vs Parligras, Mircea Emilian (19th European Team Championship, Warsaw, 2013)"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3
Ne4 9. Nd2 Nxg3 10. hxg3 c6 11. a3 Bf8 12. e3 Bg7
{ In the course I recommended  12...Be6  with the plan to go for the long castle. However, the text is also fine. My plan in this game was to castle short. }
13. Bd3 Nd7 14. Bf5
{ It's not clear how White should proceed, but I was happy with the bishops being traded.   14.O-O  O-O  15.Rc1  Re8∞   14.b4  O-O  15.O-O  Re8  16.Rb1  a6∞  this is fully playable for Black. }
14... Qe7 15. Qe2 Nb6 16. Bxc8 Rxc8 17. b4 O-O 18. O-O Rce8
{ I decided to go for an attack, but this also helps White with the minority attack.   18...Rfe8=  would have been more cautious. }
19. Qd3 f5 20. Ne2 { 20.Nf3  looks more natural. } 20... Nc8
{ A nice regrouping - d6 is an excellent spot for the knight. } 21. Rab1 Nd6
22. a4 a6 23. Nb3 { 23.Nf3  again, this looks more natural. } 23... Rf7 24. Nc5
Bf8 { 24...h5  was more direct. } 25. Rb3 { 25.Nc3∞ } 25... Qf6 26. Qd1 h5 27.
Nd3 Nc4
{ I wanted to stop Ne5, but I allowed b5.   27...Qe6!  28.Ne5  Rh7∓  would lead to an advantage. I had to keep the knight on d6 in order to avoid White's counterplay.   27...Rh7!  this is the same thing. }
28. b5 axb5 29. axb5 Rh7 30. bxc6 bxc6 31. Nb2
{ 31.Ne5!  sacrifices a pawn, but eases off the tension.  31...Nxe5  32.dxe5  Rxe5  33.Nd4=∞  with good compensation for the pawn. }
31... Qh6
{ After this White will be able to parry the attack.   31...Na5!  gains a tempo on the attack, but I didn't like my knight at the edge of the board.  32.Rb6  h4  with an attack.  33.g4  Bd6!  the white king is in big trouble. }
32. Nxc4 dxc4 33. Rb6
{ 33.Rc3!?  deserved attention.  33...h4  34.Qa4  without fear of getting checkmated.  34...hxg3  35.Qxc4+  Kh8  36.fxg3  f4∞  the position remains complex. }
33... h4 34. g4 h3 35. g3 h2+
{ 35...Qe6!  was a better try.  36.Nc3  fxg4  37.Qe2∞  it's not clear how to proceed as the attack petered out. }
36. Kh1 Qe6 37. Nc3 fxg4 38. d5 Qe5 39. Qd4 Qf5 40. f3 gxf3 41. dxc6 Qc2 42.
Qd5+ Kh8 43. Qxf3 Qxc3 44. c7 Qe5
{ During the game I had seen this move, but I was looking for other options to try to win. It's the only way to make a draw! }
45. Qxf8+ Rxf8 46. Rxf8+ Kg7 47. Rg8+ Kf7 48. Rf8+ Kg7 49. Rg8+
{ An interesting and exciting game that proves the 5... g5 line is fully playable. }
