[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "6. Ding Liren vs Parligras, Mircea (40th Chess Olympiad, Istanbul, 2012)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4
{ These were my early days with the Ragozin when I didn't have as much experience with it. }
5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. Bg5 h6
{ 6...dxc4!?  this is an option mentioned in the course. } 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. e3
O-O 9. Be2 Bd7 10. Qb3 dxc4 11. Qxc4 Qg6
{ The old continuation, which is also possible. In the course I recommended  11...Qe7  . }
12. O-O Bd6 13. Nb5
{ 13.Rfd1  the main line.  13...Na5  14.Qd3  Qxd3  15.Bxd3  Rfd8  White has a slight pressure in this endgame, but it's nothing special. Black is very solid. All the games in my database ended in a draw! }
13... Rac8
{ I wanted to be prepared if he takes on d6.   13...e5!  was called for, but I was afraid his queen could enter the 7th rank.  14.Nxd6  cxd6  15.d5  Ne7  16.Rfc1  b6=  17.Qc7  this is not dangerous.  17...Rfd8 }
14. Rac1 Be7
{ This was an unpunished blunder. My idea was to play ...a6 and get rid of his knight. However, we both missed }
15. a3
{ Not a bad move in itself, but it misses a tactical strike.   15.Nxa7±  very nice, an unusual motif. White wins a pawn.  15...Ra8   15...Nxa7  16.Ne5!  the point.  16.Nb5  the knight is there to stay - there is no more ...a6.  16...Rfc8  17.Rfd1± }
15... a6 16. Nc3 Bd6 17. Rfd1
{ White is still slightly better because it's not easy for me to show some counterplay. }
17... Ne7 { Rerouting the knight to d5. } 18. g3
{ 18.e4!?  it deserves attention to prevent ...Nd5.  18...Bb5  19.Nxb5  axb5  20.Qc2  c6  21.Bd3⩲ }
18... Nd5 19. Nh4
{ 19.Nxd5  doesn't win a pawn.  19...Bb5!  this is the trick - I will trade the bishops on e2 and then take back the knight.  20.Ne5!?  Qg5  the queen is safe here.   20...Bxe5?  21.Ne7++-  21.Qc2  Bxe2  22.Qxe2  exd5=  with an equal position. }
19... Qg5 20. Ne4 Qe7 21. Qb3 Nb6 22. Nc3 a5 23. Bf3 Rb8 24. Be4 Rfd8 25. Bb1
Be8 26. d5
{ This push only opens up the position for my bishops. White had to continue maneuvering to maintain a slightly better position.   26.Nf3⩲ }
26... Nxd5 27. Nxd5 exd5 28. Rxd5
{ 28.Nf5!  was the way to go, in order to include the knight into play.  28...Qf6  29.Rxd5  White is in the game. }
28... a4 { Good timing - it fixes the weakness on b2. } 29. Qd3 g6
{ It turns out my king is actually safe. } 30. Rd1 Bc6
{ Here I had to be accurate, and I saw the sacrifice on g6 doesn't work. } 31.
Rd4 Qf6 32. Qc4
{ White's position is bad, his knight is stranded on h4. However the text just loses.   32.Ba2  would continue the fight.  32...Kg7∓ }
32... Be5 { The b2-pawn will be lost, and with it the game. } 33. Rxd8+ Rxd8
34. Rxd8+ Qxd8 35. Be4 Qd1+ 36. Kg2 Qb3 { A nice detail. } 37. Qxb3 Bxe4+
{ A big success for me in the Ragozin. It's one of those games that made me analyze the opening further, and also one of the reasons that determined me to write this course. The tactical trick that we both missed is also instructive. }
