[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "7. Keymer, Vincent vs Aronian, Levon (Berlin FIDE Grand Prix 2022, Berlin, 2022)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. e3 O-O 7. Qc2 Qe7
{ This is the main game from one of our lines. Levon Aronian is an experienced Ragozin player, and here he introduced into practice a new idea - a novelty on move 7 in 2022! }
8. Bd2 dxc4 9. Bxc4 e5 10. d5 Qc5 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Ne7 13. Nxe5 Bf5 14.
Qf4 Bxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Qb4+
{ 15...g6  this is recommended in the course, when Black is slightly better. }
16. Kc1 Qc5 17. g4
{ 17.Kd2  I wonder if Levon would have repeated the moves or continued the game.  17...g6!  keeps the game going. }
17... g5
{ The bishop doesn't have good retreats, so extreme measures are called for! The idea is to deflect the queen from defending the bishop.   17...Bg6?  18.Nd7+- }
18. b4
{ Great stuff. Another deflection idea, in order to play Qd4.   18.Qxg5+  Bg6  the point is there is no Nd7 anymore because the c4-bishop is not defended.  19.Qf4  b5  the bishop is doomed anyway.  20.Nd7  Qxc4+  21.Qxc4  bxc4  22.Nxf8  Kxf8⩱  favours Black. }
18... Qxb4 19. Qd4 Ng6
{ Counts on the white queen being overloaded.   19...Bg6  the natural bishop retreat.  20.a3!?  Qa4  21.Nxg6  Nxg6  22.Kb2∞  leads to an unusual, complicated position. }
20. Bb3 Qa3+ 21. Kd2 c5 { It looks nice to include this! } 22. Qc3 Nxe5 23.
gxf5 { Forced. } 23... Rfe8 24. Rhg1 b5
{ Just pushing. The idea is good, but here it's slow.   24...h6∞  also playable.   24...Nf3+?  this only speeds up White's attack.  25.Ke2  Nxg1+  26.Rxg1  Qa6+  27.Kd2±  with a strong attack.   24...c4!? }
25. Rxg5+ Kh8 26. Bd1
{ Let's Black back in the game.   26.Rag1!  it was essential to bring the last piece into the attack. The threat is Rg8+.  26...f6  27.R5g3!  c4  28.Bc2±  White is going to push the central pawns with a big edge. }
26... Qa6 27. Be2 Rad8
{ Levon manages to create threats, not giving Vincent time to play Rag1. } 28.
e4 Qa4 29. Rh5
{ A blunder in a chaotic position. It's easy to go wrong here, but the e4-pawn had to be defended anyway!   29.Ke3  domehow there is no way to punish the brave white king.  29...f6  30.Rg3  Rxd5  31.f3∞  with an unclear position.   29.f3  another way to defend e4.  29...b4∞ }
29... Qxe4
{ Now it's all over - White's position simply crumbles down, leaving the king exposed. }
30. Rg1 { 30.Qh3  Qxd5+-+  and mate to follow.  31.Ke1  Qh1+  32.Bf1  Nf3 }
30... Rxd5+ 31. Kc1 Qf4+
{ Accurate - it parries both threats of Rxh7+ and Qh3, and the immediate Qg3. }
32. Kb1 Rd4 33. Bxb5 { 33.Qg3  Rb4+-+  it is game over anyway. } 33... Rb4+
{ White loses a piece and the game. } 34. Ka1 Rxb5 35. Re1 f6
{ A thrilling game, where good calculation skills were required. It shows that the Ragozin can lead to sharp positions as well! }
