[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "8. Dreev, Alexey vs Carlsen, Magnus (FIDE World Cup, Tblisi, 2017)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. Qb3 c5 8.
cxd5 exd5 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 c4 11. b3 Be6 12. Ne5 O-O 13. e3 Nc6
{ 13...Nd7!  in the course I recommended this as slightly more precise than the game. With the c-file open we can meet  14.bxc4  with  14...dxc4  . }
14. Be2
{ An understandable decision - White wants to complete development.   14.bxc4!  this looks risky but it was possible.  14...Nxe5   but not  14...dxc4  because of  15.Nxc6  bxc6  16.Bxc4  .  15.dxe5  Qg6  16.c5!  the only chance is to close the game.  16...Rac8↑  White still has some problems because the king is stuck in the center. }
14... Nxe5 15. dxe5 Qg6 16. O-O d4
{ A good practical decision, forcing the events. Black gets a strong pawn on b3.   16...Rfd8⩱  was also possible. }
17. exd4 cxb3 18. Bf3
{ This logical move is too slow.   18.Bd3!  was a better option.  18...Qg4  19.Bc4!  this is the point - White manages to trade the bishops.  19...Rac8  20.Bxe6  Qxe6  21.Qb4∞  White is in the game here, although I still prefer Black due to the b3-pawn. }
18... Rac8 19. Qe3 Qg5
{ It's tempting to go for a pleasant endgame, but this gives away part of the advantage.   19...Bc4!  was the most accurate move. The idea is to bring the queen to b6.  20.Rfd1  Qb6  21.Rab1  a5  the b3-pawn gives Black an edge. }
20. Rab1 Qxe3 21. fxe3 Rfd8 { Sacrifices a pawn in order to stop d5. } 22. Bxb7
Rc3 23. d5 Bd7 24. Rf4
{ The idea is to go Rb4, but this can be easily stopped.   24.d6!  was called for, in order to bring the bishop to d5.  24...Be6  25.Rfd1  Rc5!?   25...Rxe3  26.Bd5=  26.e4  the bishop will get to d5 after all.  26...Rxe5  27.Bd5  Rxd6  28.Rxb3= }
24... a5 25. Kf2
{ 25.d6!  was the only chance.  25...Be6  26.Rd4  Rb8  27.Bd5  b2  looks bad for White. }
25... Rb8 { The b3-pawn is supported and Black wins easily. } 26. Bc6 Bxc6 27.
dxc6 Rxc6 28. Rd4 Rc2+ 29. Kf3 b2 30. Rdd1 Rb5 31. a4 Rxe5 32. Rd8+ Kh7
{ A clear victory by Magnus! After this game the line lost in popularity and White started to look for other ways to fight for an advantage in the Ragozin. }
