[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "9. Rogozenco, Dorian vs Parligras, Mircea-Emilian (Romanian Superliga, Oradea, 2022)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd2 dxc4 8.
Bxc4 a6 9. Qc2 Bd6 10. a3 e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. f4 Bxc3 14. Bxc3
Ng4 15. Bd4 c5 16. Bxc5 Re8 17. O-O Nxe3 18. Bxe3 Rxe3 19. Rfe1 Rxe1+
{ 19...Qd4  it was tempting not to give up the e-file, but it gives White chances.  20.Qf2  Rxe1+  21.Rxe1  Qxf2+  22.Kxf2  Kf8  23.Bd5⩲  with a pleasant endgame for White. }
20. Rxe1 b5 21. Qe4 Bd7 22. Bd5 Rc8
{ A logical move found over the board. I knew the position is equal but that I had to be accurate, and I took my time to consider his replies.   22...Qb6+  this is given in the course.  23.Qe3   23.Kh1  Rf8=  looks fine for Black. ...h6 is a useful move to prepare ...Re8.  23...Qxe3+   23...Rb8!?  24.Rxe3  Rc8  25.Bb7   25.Re7  transposes to the game.  25...Rb8=  if the bishop retreats there is ...Kf8.  26.Bxa6  Kf8!  the king is needed in the center, and now the white bishop can be in trouble.  27.Rc3  Ke8!  the king goes to d8 and then there is the threat of ...Rb6. White has to give back the pawn to save his bishop.  28.Rc7?  this is wrong due to  28...Ra8! }
23. Qe7
{ I was expecting this, as it's the most forcing move.   23.b4  Qf6!?  or  23...Qb6  with an equal position. I don't see how White can attack the a6-pawn. }
23... Qxe7 24. Rxe7 Be6
{ The most straightforward continuation, although it involves a pawn sac.   24...Be8  should hold as well, but I was afraid my pieces could be too passive.  25.b4  Kf8  26.Ra7  Rd8!  27.Bf3  Rd4  28.Rxa6  Rxf4=  the ending is equal. }
25. Bxe6 { 25.Rxe6?  this is wrong due to.  25...Rc1+!  26.Kf2  fxe6-+ } 25...
Rc1+
{ It's important to give these checks while White cannot cover them with the rook. }
26. Kf2 Rc2+ 27. Kf3 fxe6 28. Rxe6 Rxb2 29. Rxa6 Rb3+
{ My idea was to force the white king to h3.   29...b4=  it was also possible to exchange the last pawns on the queenside. The 3v2 endgame is an easy draw. }
30. Ke4
{ 30.Kg4  Rb2  31.Kh3  b4  sooner or later I have to exchange the pawns.  32.axb4  Rxb4=  with an equal 3v2 endgame. }
30... Rb2 31. Rb6
{ 31.g4!?  I was calculating this during the game.  31...Rxh2  32.g5  g6=  the ending is just equal. }
31... Rxg2 32. Rxb5 Ra2
{ I wanted to avoid his pawn getting to the 5th rank.   32...Rxh2  this is also possible.  33.a4  Ra2  34.a5  Kf7=  with an easy draw. }
33. Rb8+ { 33.Ra5  Rxh2  34.a4  Ra2=  the endgame is completely equal. } 33...
Kf7 34. Rb7+ Kf6 35. Rb6+ Kf7
{ Although I didn't remember all the details during the game, it was important that I was familiar with the positions and I found quite easily a clear path to equality. }
