[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "10. Indjic, Aleksandar vs Navara, David (23rd European Chess Championship, Terme Catez, 2021)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Bd7 8.
cxd5 exd5 9. Qc2 Na5 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bxf6
{ Quite a modest move. In the course the more principled  11.Bh4  is given. }
11... Qxf6 12. Ne5
{ White goes for activity without finishing development.   12.e3  this natural move was preferable.  12...O-O  ...c5 is Black's idea here.  13.Ne5!?  Bf5  14.Bd3  Bxd3  15.Qxd3=  with an equal position. The threat of Nd7 can easily be parried. }
12... Bf5 13. Qa4+ Nc6 14. e3 O-O
{ It turns out it was useful for Black to bring the knight back to c6. I think White's opening strategy failed. }
15. Nf3
{ 15.Nd3  was the better retreat.  15...b6  16.Be2  Na5=  with an equal position. }
15... a6
{ A good idea to grab some space on the queenside.   15...Ne7!?  this is a typical regrouping move. Black is ready to push ...c5-c4 to gain space on the queenside.  16.Be2  c5  with ...c4 next, and Black has a space advantage. }
16. Be2 b5 17. Qd1 Na5 { The knight will be ideally placed on c4. } 18. O-O Nc4
19. Nd2 Rfe8 20. Nb3 { The knight is heading to c5. } 20... Qg5
{ 20...Nb2!?  it was interesting to relocate the knight to a4 to prevent Nc5.  21.Qd2  Na4⩱  White's position is passive, and he's lacking a plan. }
21. Nc5
{ White's knight is strong, controlling important squares like e4 and e6. Thus it's not easy for Black to bring a rook on the 6th rank in order to start an attack. }
21... Bh3 22. Bf3 h5
{ The idea is to play ...Bg4 to trade the bishops.   22...c6!?  defending the pawn would give White time to play either Kh1, or Re1 preparing e4. }
23. Ra2
{ 23.Bxd5  it looked dangerous to grab a pawn but weaken the king. In a practical game I would also have refrained from it.  23...Qxd5  24.gxh3  Nd6=∞  with a long term compensation. }
23... Bg4 24. Kh1 a5 25. h3 Bxf3 26. gxf3
{ A good decision - White is changing the pawn structure and tries to get some play.   26.Qxf3  a4∓  White is lacking counterplay. }
26... Reb8
{ This looks counterintuitive, but the rook is heading towards the kingside via b6.   26...Qf5  27.Kh2  Re7  was a bit more accurate. After doubling on the e-file there are ideas of ...Nxe3. }
27. Qe2
{ 27.Rg1  it looks more natural to get control over the g-file at once.  27...Qf5  28.Kh2  Rb6  29.f4∞  White managed to activate his pieces. If  29...Rg6  there is  30.Qb1! }
27... Rb6 { Continuing the plan. } 28. Rg1 Qf5 29. Kh2 Re8 30. f4 Rg6
{ It's important to trade White's active rook! } 31. Rxg6 Qxg6 32. Ra1 Qf5
{ ...Qxf4+ is the threat! } 33. Nd3 f6
{ Black can slowly improve his position. } 34. Kg2 c6 35. Kh2 g6 36. h4
{ This pawn will be a weakness later on.   36.a4∓  good or bad, White had to go for this sooner or later. }
36... Kh7 37. Kg3 Kh6 38. Kh2 a4
{ Although the material is equal, I think White's position is hopeless due to the many weaknesses - a3 and h4. }
39. Kg2 Qe4+ 40. Kh2 Re7 41. Kg3 Nd6 42. Kh3 Nf5 43. Rg1 Qe6
{ White cannot defend the h4-pawn. } 44. Kh2 Nxh4
{ Black is winning. White is a pawn down and his king is weak. David went on to win convincingly. }
45. Rg3 Nf5 46. Rg1 Qe4 47. Qd1 Nd6 48. Nb4 Nc4 { 48...Rc7-+ } 49. Nxc6 Rc7 50.
Nb4 Nxa3 51. f3 Qf5 52. Qc1 Nc4 53. Re1 Re7 54. Kg2 g5 55. Nxd5 Qxd5 56. e4 Qd6
57. e5 fxe5 58. fxe5 Qg6
{ Simple and beautiful! It's a good lesson on how to improve a slightly better position where the opponent is lacking counterplay. }
