[White "Model Games"]
[Black "11. Kozul, Zdenko vs Gundavaa, Bayarsaihan (44th Chess Olympiad, Chennai, 2022)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. e3 O-O 8. Rc1
Nc6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. a3 Bxc3+ 11. Rxc3 Ne7
{ Not the only way to continue, but it's good to remember this maneuver. } 12.
b4
{ White starts the minority attack. Both 12. Be2 and 12. Bd3 were mentioned in the course. }
12... a6 { Prevents b5. } 13. Ne5 c6 14. Bd3 Bf5 { A good trade for Black. }
15. a4 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qe6 17. O-O Rfc8 18. Rfc1 Nf5
{ The knight is heading towards d6. } 19. Qb1
{ 19.b5?  doesn't work. It was also mentioned in the course.  19...axb5  20.axb5  c5∓  the pawn will advance further to c4, and White cannot take it because of the weakness of the first rank. }
19... Nd6
{ Now b5 is stopped for good and Black has a free hand on the kingside. } 20.
h3 Re8
{ Black can slowly improve the position by pushing the pawns on the kingside. Of course, it's not easy to achieve something, but White can only sit and watch. }
21. Rb3 { This gives Black an additional opportunity. } 21... Nc4
{ 21...h5⩱  simply pushing on the kingside was also possible. } 22. Nxc4
{ Now Black is getting a strong c4-pawn.   22.Nf3  was a better option. } 22...
dxc4 23. Ra3 b5
{ The c4-pawn is strong and is there to stay. Black can prepare to push ...f5 to open up the position. }
24. Qb2 Qd6 25. Rca1 Re6 26. f3
{ 26.axb5  it was better to clarify the situation on the queenside.  26...cxb5  27.f3  f5  28.Qc3⩱  White is holding on, but Black still has ideas. }
26... f5
{ 26...Rae8!?  27.e4  Qf4  was interesting, in order to take back on b5 with the a-pawn. }
27. h4
{ The h-pawn is loose!   27.axb5  again, this exchange was called for.  27...cxb5  28.Qc3⩱ }
27... Rae8 { Suddenly White is just lost. } 28. axb5 axb5 29. Qd2 Qe7
{ White cannot avoid losing a pawn. } 30. h5 Rxe3 31. Rxe3 Qxe3+ 32. Qxe3 Rxe3
{ The endgame is hopeless for White. } 33. Ra6 Rb3 34. Rxc6 Rxb4 35. Rc7 Rb2
36. d5 Kf8 37. Kf1 Rd2 38. Rc5 b4 39. Ke1 { 39.Rxc4  b3  40.Rb4  b2-+ } 39...
c3 40. Rc4 Rxg2 41. Rxb4 Rg1+
{ A nice strategical game! This is the kind of game that made me recommend the ...Nc6 line for Black. }
