1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Bd7 8.
cxd5 exd5 9. Bf4 O-O 10. e3 Ne5 11. Qb3 Nxf3+ 12. gxf3 b6 13. Rg1 Re8
{ Until here it was given in the course. The conclusion was that we reached an interesting and unbalanced position. }
14. Be2
{ 14.Be5!?  it was tempting to go for this immediately.  14...g6!?  an interesting pawn sacrifice.   14...c6  this is similar to the game.  15.Bd3  the bishop is more active here than on e2.  15...g6  16.Ke2∞  White can try to organize an attack with h4, but the position remains unclear.  15.Bxf6  otherwise Black goes ...c5.  15...Qxf6  16.Qxd5  Bf5⇆  followed by ...Rad8 with good compensation. The white king is exposed. }
14... c6 15. Be5 g6 16. a4 { Just to gain some space. } 16... Bf5 17. Kd2
{ A logical move, connecting the rooks.   17.Qa3!?  c5  18.a5∞  with an unbalanced position with chances for both sides. }
17... Rxe5
{ A tempting sacrifice, which spices up the game.   17...c5!  was stronger, as there was no need to give up material.  18.h4  Nh5∞  with an unbalanced position. The white king is in the center but it's not easy to get to it. }
18. dxe5 Nd7 19. Qb4
{ The best defense, activating the queen and stopping ...Qh4.   19.f4?!  it's not good to hold onto the e5-pawn because the white pieces will get very passive.  19...Nc5  20.Qb2  Qh4  21.f3  Rd8⩱  Black keeps a strong initiative. }
19... Nxe5 20. Qf4 Nc4+ 21. Ke1 Qf6
{ 21...Nd6=∞  I think it would have been a good idea to keep the knight on the board. }
22. Qd4 Qe7 23. e4
{ 23.Bxc4  dxc4  24.Qxc4  Rd8=∞  it's not easy for White to coordinate his pieces. }
23... Re8 24. Bxc4 dxc4 25. Rd1
{ 25.Qe3  was also good.  25...Qh4  Black keeps some compensation but it's probably not enough. }
25... Qh4 26. Qd6
{ A seemingly active move that allows Black to make a draw.   26.Qd2!  a nice retreat with the idea to go Qg5!  26...Qxh2  27.Qg5  Be6  28.Ke2  White has an advantage, but things are still not clear. }
26... Rxe4+ { Black saves himself with a perpetual check. } 27. fxe4 Qxe4+ 28.
Kd2 Qc2+ 29. Ke3 Qe4+ 30. Kd2 Qc2+ 31. Ke1 Qe4+ 32. Kd2
{ An exciting game, and let's not forget it was rapid! Shakhriyar sacrificed an exchange in a good position, White defended well and finally the game ended in a draw. }
