1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3 dxc4 7. Bxc4 c5 8. O-O
cxd4 9. exd4 b6 10. Bg5 Bxc3
{ I think it's too early to go for this exchange.   10...Bb7  this is what I recommended in the course. }
11. bxc3 Bb7 12. Qe2
{ 12.Bd3!?  White should go like this, or even 12. Re1 first.  12...Nbd7  13.c4  Qc7  with the idea ...Ng4.  14.Re1⩲  White has a grip and it's not so easy for Black to create counterplay.  14...Ng4?!  doesn't work with the rook on e1.  15.h3!  Bxf3?  16.Qxf3  Qh2+?  17.Kf1  Ngf6  18.Bf4+- }
12... Nbd7 13. Rac1
{ 13.Bd3  now there is no time for this regrouping.  13...Qc7  14.c4  Ng4  15.Be4  Bxe4  16.Qxe4  Ngf6=  the position is about equal since Black managed to trade the light-squared bishops. }
13... Qc7 { We got back to the course. } 14. Nd2 Nd5 15. Bxd5 exd5 16. Rfe1 f6
{ This is also good. In the long run, Black will be able to fight for the e-file.   16...h6  this is what I recommended in the course. }
17. Bh4
{ 17.Qe6+  only helps Black regroup his pieces.  17...Rf7  18.Bh4  Nf8= } 17...
Qc6 { Anticipates Bg3. } 18. Nf1 Rf7
{ 18...Rae8  it's not easy to evaluate the consequences of this move.  19.Qxe8   19.Ne3∞  with a normal position.  19...Rxe8  20.Rxe8+  Kf7  21.Ree1∞  with an unbalanced position, where it seems the queen is no worse than 2 rooks.   21.Rce1?!  fails to  21...Ne5! }
19. Bg3 Nf8 20. h4 Qd7
{ Black wants to play ...Bc6 and ...Re8 to take control over the e-file. } 21.
h5 Bc6 { 21...h6  was more cautious. } 22. Ne3
{ Around here Vidit missed his chance to fight for an advantage.   22.Qf3  prepares h6 and doesn't allow Black to trade the bishop for the knight with ...Bb5.  22...h6  23.Ne3⩲  Black cannot parry both c4 and Nf5.   22.h6!?  this could be considered.  22...Bb5  23.Qf3  Bxf1  24.Kxf1⩲  White's position looks preferable. }
22... Re8 23. Qf3 { 23.c4  was preferable, in order to open up the game. }
23... f5 { The right move to get counterplay. The threat is ...f4. } 24. Nf1
{ 24.Bf4  Re4⇆  followed by ...Ne6 looks good for Black. } 24... Re4
{ What a big difference compared to a few moves ago! Black got control over the e-file and activated his pieces a great deal. }
25. Be5 Ne6 { 25...h6!?  could be considered, just to stop the pawn push. } 26.
Qd1
{ White is cautious and prevents future ...Ng5 ideas.   26.h6  Rh4!?  looks quite dangerous for White.  27.Bxg7!   27.hxg7?  f4→  with a powerful attack.  27...Nxg7  28.hxg7  Qd6=  the resulting position is about equal. }
26... Rxe1 27. Qxe1 f4 28. f3 h6 { Finally Black stops the h-pawn. } 29. Qh4
{ 29.Nh2  this was a good moment to bring the knight into play.  29...Bb5  30.Ng4=  with a roughly equal game. }
29... Rf5 { Going after the h5-pawn. ...Qf7 is next. } 30. g4
{ Not a move you want to make, but how else to defend the h5-pawn? } 30... Rxe5
{ A nice exchange sac for the initiative.   30...Ng5  the move order could be changed.  31.Nh2  Rxe5!   30...fxg3?!  31.f4⇆  this is the point. White is not even in a hurry to take back the g3-pawn, actually, Ne3 is next. }
31. dxe5 d4
{ 31...Ng5!  the knight has to join the attack anyway.  32.Nh2  d4  33.Kf1  dxc3∓  White has a difficult task ahead defending this position.  34.Rxc3?  loses on the spot.  34...Qd1+  otherwise ...Qd2+ wins the rook.  35.Qe1  Bb5+  36.Kf2  Nh3+-+  the decisive check - White loses the queen. }
32. Nh2 d3 { 32...Ng5!  was more precise, transposing to the previous line. }
33. Rd1 { 33.Qf2  Ng5  34.Kf1=∞  it seems that White can defend. } 33... Ng5
34. Kg2 { Here Vidit found good defensive resources to stay in the game. }
34... d2 35. e6 { The saving move. } 35... Qxe6
{ 35...Nxe6  the knight leaves its active position, which gives White enough time to go after the d2-pawn.  36.Qf2!  Ng5  37.Rxd2  Bxf3+  38.Nxf3  Qxg4+  39.Kf1  Nxf3  40.Rd8+  Kf7  41.Rd3=  with a likely draw. }
36. Rxd2 Kh7 37. Rd4 Bxf3+ 38. Nxf3 Nxf3 39. Kxf3 Qe3+ 40. Kg2 f3+ 41. Kh3 Qe2
42. Qg3 f2 43. Rf4 f1=Q+ 44. Rxf1 Qxf1+ 45. Kh2
{ The queen endgame is an easy draw, but Black managed to win it somehow. }
45... Qe2+ 46. Qg2 Qe5+ 47. Qg3 Qd5 48. Qf2 Qe4 49. Kg3 Qe5+ 50. Kg2 Qxc3 51.
Qf5+ Kg8 52. Qe6+
{ 52.Qd5+!  it was easier to give the checks like this.  52...Kf8   52...Kh8  53.Qa8+  Kh7  54.Qe4+=  53.Qa8+=  with an obvious draw - White will take the b6-pawn. }
52... Kf8 53. Qd6+ Kf7 54. Qd7+ Kf6 55. Qxa7 Qd4 56. Kg3 Qe3+ 57. Kg2
{ 57.Kh4= } 57... Qe4+ 58. Kg3 Qe5+ 59. Kg2
{ 59.Kh3=  from a practical point of view it was easier to keep the king closer to the pawn.  59...Kg5  60.Qxb6  with a draw. }
59... b5 60. Qf2+ Kg5 61. Qg3
{ Probably a mistake in time trouble.   61.Kh3=  was called for. Again, the king has to stay close to the pawn.  61...Qc3+  62.Qg3  b4  63.Kh2  leads to a draw. }
61... Qe4+ { But now White is in trouble. } 62. Kf2
{ 62.Kh2!  this is the only move. White is much worse, but can hope to save the game after a tough defense.  62...b4!?   62...Qxg4  63.Qe5+!  Qf5  64.Qxg7+  Kxh5  65.Qd4=  looks close to equal.   62...Qd5∓  keeps an advantage.  63.a3  bxa3  64.Qxa3  Qe2+  65.Kg3  Qxg4+  66.Kh2  Kxh5∓  this should be a draw, but only with correct play. In a practical game Black is 2 pawns up and has good chances to win. }
62... Qf4+ 63. Qf3 b4
{ Zugzwang. White cannot avoid losing the g4-pawn and the queen trade. An exciting game, which shows that even apparently calm positions can lead to a very interesting fight. }
