1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 O-O 5. e3 d5 6. Bd2 b6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Bd3
Bb7 9. Ne5 Bd6 10. O-O c5 11. Rc1 Nc6 12. Ng4 Nd7
{ Black doesn't want to trade the knights. The idea is to go after the g4-knight with ...h5 or ...f5. The knight seems more active on d7 than on e8, but it allows a tactical strike!   12...Ne8!  this is my recommendation in the course. }
13. Nh6+
{ A nice sacrifice, which leads to a long, forced line. Black's king is in big danger. Good calculation skills are called for in this instance, since if you miss something it's game over.   13.f4  a typical move, but it leaves the d4-pawn undefended.  13...cxd4  14.exd4  Nxd4  15.Be3  Nc6  16.Nxd5  Ne7  17.Nxe7+  Bxe7∞  Black should be fine here.   13.Nxd5?  this is wrong due to  (13...f5∓.) }
13... gxh6
{ The sacrifice must be accepted.   13...Kh8?  14.Qh5±  gives White a strong attack. }
14. Qg4+ { White is going to attack h7, the weak spot in Black's position. }
14... Kh8 15. Qf5 Nf6 { The only defense. } 16. Nxd5 { This is the point. }
16... Nxd4 { Forced. Black has to get rid of the d5-knight. } 17. Qxf6+
{ It's time to get back some material.   17.exd4?  this is wrong.  17...Bxd5-+  White's attack peters out. }
17... Qxf6 18. Nxf6 Nf3+
{ Luckily Black has this resource.   18...Be5?!  19.exd4  Bxf6  20.dxc5±  it's a bad endgame for Black. }
19. gxf3 Rg8+ 20. Ng4
{ Only like this. Now White has a strong threat of Bc3+.   20.Nxg8?  Rxg8+  21.Kh1  Bxf3 }
20... Be5
{ Another important detail - the long diagonal must be secured before taking back the piece. }
21. Be2 Bxb2
{ Black keeps the game entertaining!   21...h5  22.Bc3  Bxc3  23.Rxc3  hxg4  24.fxg4⩲  leaves White a pawn up, but Black has compensation. }
22. Rxc5
{ And Wei Yi rises to the challenge! White will take back some material after Rb1, when one of the bishops falls.   22.Rc2  Bf6=  followed by ...h5, with a roughly equal position.  23.Kh1?  this is not possible because of the long diagonal pin, as it allows  23...Rxg4 }
22... bxc5 23. Rb1 Bg7 { The safest place for the bishop. } 24. Rxb7 h5 25.
Rxf7
{ 25.Bc4!  was the way to fight for an advantage.  25...hxg4  26.fxg4  Rab8  27.Rxf7  Rgf8  28.Rxf8+  Bxf8  29.Kg2⩲  I like White's chances in this ending, although it may end up in a draw nevertheless. }
25... hxg4 26. fxg4 Rgf8 { 26...Rab8  27.Bc4⩲  leads to the previous line. }
27. Rxf8+ Rxf8 { The ending is about equal because Black's pieces are active. }
28. Kf1 Rb8 29. Bc4 Rb1+ 30. Ke2 Rh1 { The h2-pawn will drop. } 31. Bd5 Rxh2
32. g5 Rh5 33. e4 Bd4 34. Bf4
{ 34.f4  h6!?  it's good to exchange some pawns.  35.gxh6   35.g6?  Kg7-+  White's pawns are stuck, while the h-pawn will be very dangerous.  35...Rxh6=  the position simplified and it's just equal. }
34... Kg7 35. e5 Kf8 36. Bf3 Rh4 37. Bg3 Rh3 38. Bg2 Rxg3 39. fxg3 Bxe5 40. Be4
{ A very nice fight! This line can be dangerous for Black, and I recommend studying it carefully. The inaccurate 12... Nd7 led Black into trouble, and only a long and resourceful defense managed to save him the game. }
